<H2>The winds of  change</H2>
 The health system has changed dramatically since the GVRD  Hospital Planning 
 and Development Board held its first  meeting in 1967. Over the last 30 
 years, the region has  cost-shared in over $800 million for hospital 
 buildings,  renovations and equipment. This capital development has  been 
 guided by regional health plans and supported by the  GVRD Hospital Planning 
 and Development Department in its  capital funding and planning role.
 
 <P>
 
<CENTER><IMG ALIGN=left SRC="../../hospital/av_media/hosp.gif"></CENTER>
<P>
<I>The GVRD Hospital Planning and Development Department  contributed $6.2 million 
toward a new extended care  building at the Peace Arch Pavilion Hospital.  
This  building incorporates some of the newest design  philosophies and 
offers state-of-the-art features. 
</I>
<P><BR>
<BR><BR><BR>
Today, the department  continues to keep pace with  the changing health system  
and is moving from its early  role of strict capital  allocation to include  
program planning and  regional evaluation. It  understands that effective  
regional planning means  major programs, services and  equipment are maximized, 
not  duplicated.
<P>
Over the coming years, the  department's role will  continue to evolve as it  
adds value to the planning  process and assists the  Regional Health Boards 
with  their program delivery   decisions. To meet these  future challenges, 
the  department is currently  developing a strategic  plan.
As we look to the future,  this Health Planning Review  highlights activities 
within  the Acute Care,  Rehabilitation, Psychiatry,  Obstetrics and Perinatal  
subcommittees over the past  18 months.  

<P>
It also summarizes how  projected changes within the  GVRD will impact health 
 planning, and it reviews  some of the capital planning  activities and 
 associated  cost savings.  We trust you  will find this review  informative. 



<P>
<BR><BR>

<H2>Health  services 
planning -
subcommittee  
reports
 </H2>


<H4><A NAME="acute1">Acute  care</H4></A><P>

A key goal of acute  care planning is to  ensure the equitable  allocation of 
resources  within the GVRD. 
The Regional Acute Care  Bed Plan was recently  updated to incorporate  
population projections  reflected in the GVRD's  Livable Region  Strategic 
Plan. As  well, a new utilization   target of 650 bed days  per 1,000 population  
was established to  reflect the declining  use patterns 
throughout  BC.  Results indicate  that the region's bed  requirements are  
sufficient  up to the  year 2006, with the  exception of the South  
Fraser Valley. In that  area, the plan  identified a shortage  of 
approximately 100  beds by 2001.

<P>

The subcommittee also  recognizes that acute in-patient  beds are becoming 
less  important as we see  increases in day  surgery and ambulatory  care. 
A current study  in day surgery examines  required resources to  meet future 
needs and  the impact of those  programs on in-patient  beds.

 <P>
 
 <BR><BR>
<H4><A NAME="rehab1">Rehabilitation </A>
</H4>

Planning focused on  developing a more  effective means of  gathering, sharing 
and  using information for  planning rehabilitation  services. 
As a result, an  information catalogue  was compiled and  distributed. In  
addition, the  Rehabilitation  sub-committee  commissioned a survey  of 
consumers in five  rehabilitation agencies  to assess their  priorities for  
rehabilitation  outcomes. 
The most significant  finding was agreement  that the top priority  was for 
patients to  achieve a self-directed  lifestyle. Currently,  the sub-committee 
is  reviewing future   rehabilitation bed  requirements. 


<P>
<BR><BR>

<H4><A NAME="obste1">Obstetrics</A></H4> 


A report projecting  maternity bed  requirements for 2001   and 2006 was 
released.  The report factors  recent changes in  maternity care such as  
shorter hospital stays,  shifts in birth volumes  and declining cesarean  
section rates. Results  indicate that, except  for the South Fraser  Valley, 
the region's  bed requirements are  sufficient for the next  ten years. 
In other areas, a new  joint task group with  the Ministry of Health  is 
examining issues and  concepts of an  alternative birthing  model called 
Single  Room Maternity Care. 

<P>
<BR><BR>
<H4><A NAME="psyc1">Psychiatry</A></H4>

 
A key activity was the  development of a long   range plan for acute  care 
psychiatry bed  needs within the GVRD.  The plan shows a need  for additional  
psychiatric beds in all  areas except Vancouver  and the North Shore. In  
addition, a survey of  patients in the  region's psychiatry  units revealed 
seven  per cent of patient  days were used by  patients assessed as  ready for 
discharge.
<P>
<BR><BR>

<H4><A NAME="stu1">Student  projects</A></H4>

The GVRD employed two  students from the UBC  Master of Health  Administration 
Program  to work on 1996  planning projects. One  was in the area of  
Pediatric Services  Planning, which  identified available  resources for 
asthma  care and included  recommendations for  greater integration of  
asthma management. The  other project was in  the area of   Psychogeriatric  
Services Planning. It  included a profile of  problem cases and  projections 
about  future health service  needs for this group.
<P><BR><BR>

<H2>Capital  planning</H2>


<H4><A NAME="build1">Building  Program</A></H4>

It is estimated that in  1996, the GVRD Hospital  Planning and Development  
Department and the  Ministry of Health (MOH)  will have jointly funded  
$65 million for new  facilities, renovations  and equipment. While  
expenditures are  expected to be reduced  in 1997, building  additions are 
being  planned for Surrey  Memorial Hospital, 
Zion Park and Burnaby  Hospital. The GVRD  continues to work 
with MOH and the  Regional Health Boards  to determine project  
priorites and establish  plans for future capital  and program  
developments.

<P>

<BR><BR>

<H4><A NAME="reg1">Regional  Equipment  Strategy</A></H4>
To support a  regionalized approach  to health care  planning, a long term  
strategy for high cost  medical/clinical  technology, costing  more than 
$100,000, was  completed. It is  expected this strategy  will save money by  
eliminating  duplication, reducing  overheads and improving  services. 
The strategy  also calls for a new  purchasing review  process for  
acquisitions costing  more than $100,000, to   help ensure the most  
appropriate technology  is used to meet the  identified health needs  
of the population.   

<P><BR><BR>
<H2> Regional  Services  Planning</H2>



<H4><A NAME="bio1">Biomedical  waste 
and  treatment</A></H4>

A recent review of  biomedical waste  suggests industry  developments, 
such as  increased competition  for treating and  processing biomedical  
waste, has resulted in  cost reductions of  nearly 40 per cent.   
Competitors are also  providing free waste  audits which in turn  
provides hospitals with  valuable information.  The review also found  
that under current  conditions, off-site  equipment used to treat  and 
process waste is  more cost-effective  than on-site  equipment.

<P> 
<BR><BR>

<H4>
<A NAME="food1">Food  services</A></H4>

An industry study on  shared food services  recommends phasing in  group 
purchasing of  food supplies and  moving to shared  production services.  
Already some hospitals  within the GVRD have  conducted shared food  
services trials and  have achieved savings  of approx-imately  $250,000 per 
year.  Those hospitals are now  working toward shared  production services.

<P><BR><BR>

<H4><A NAME="laund1">Laundry  services</A></H4>
The Shared Laundry  Services Task Group is  recommending  relocating services  
from Vancouver  Hospital to the  Tilbury Regional  Laundry. Studies show  
that region-wide,  shared laundry  services of this  nature can result in  
savings of $1.5 to $2   million per year.

<P><BR><BR>

<H4>
<A NAME="park1">Parking</A></H4>
Annual hospital parking  revenues of  approximately $5  million are used to  
cover operating costs,  retire parking  facilities debt  service, and reduce  
taxation levels. Some  of the many activities  underway to enhance   
customer service by  creating a more  customer friendly  environment include:
<UL>
<LI>Repainting parkade  entrance areas, cashier booths  and parking equipment
<LI>Upgrading the parking  system computer program at all  sites 
<LI>Installing credit  card facilities to 	 pay parking fees. 
</UL> 
<BR><BR>

</UL>
<H4><A NAME="fact1">GVRD facts and stats</A>
</H4>
<UL>

<LI>The use of bed days for GVRD  residents 
has decreased from 817 days  per 1,000 population in 1989 to 676 days  per 1,000 population in  1995.<P> 

<LI>The GVRD operates the largest  parking 	operation in Western Canada,  with 6,268 		parking  spaces at eight hospitals.<P>
 

<LI>There are about 130 projects  in various stages  of design and construction. The smallest is  the acquisition of wheelchairs  
	at Holy Family Hospital, and  the largest is the  construction of the Vancouver Hospital Tower.
</UL>


<BR><BR>
<H4><A NAME="list1">List of current GVRD  publications:</A>
</H4>
<UL>

	<LI>Fact Book (1996)
	<LI>Regional Equipment Strategy  (1996)
	<LI>Regional Acute Care Bed Plan  (1996)
	<LI>Maternity Bed Needs for 2001  and 2006 (1996)
	<LI>Single Room Maternity Care  Discussion Paper (1996)
	<LI>Pediatric Resources: An  Integrated Approach to  Asthma Care (1996)
	<LI>Impact of the Mentally Ill  Elderly with Severe Behaviour Problems (1996)
	<LI>Acute Care Psychiatry Long  Range Plan 
	(fall 1996)
	<LI>Discharge Assessment Survey  (fall 1996)
	<LI>A Review of Rehabilitation  Outcome 			Measures  (1995)
	<LI>Biomedical Waste (1995)
	<LI>Regional Geriatric Health  Services Plan 
	1993-2006 (1993)
</UL>
<BR><BR>
