<H2>WELCOME TO THE WORKS</H2>

<H3>With any luck, this information will cause a paper cut.</H3>

<IMG SRC="../../waste/av_media/paperstk.gif">

<IMG SRC="../../waste/av_media/bin.gif">


<P>The good news is that 75% of businesses in Greater Vancouver are already 
recycling to some degree.  The bad news is that despite this, recyclable 
paper and cardboard continue to be the main materials thrown in the garbage 
by businesses.  Whether it's paper, cardboard, aluminum or whatever, we can 
all do a better job of recycling.  Businesses have told us they want help 
starting or improving their recycling programs.  'Recycling Works' can 
provide that help.


<P>
Recycling makes good business sense.  It can save money, is good for the 
environment and is definitely good for your business' image.


<P>Each person in the Greater Vancouver Regional District generates about one 
tonne of garbage a year at work alone. A tonne. The following information
outlines simple, painless ways in which your business can do more in the 
area of recycling, whether you currently have a recycling program in place 
or not. Our goal for this first phase of the 'Recycling Works Program' is 
to double the amount of paper and cardboard currently being recycled.


<P>Reaching this goal begins by following this simple voluntary<BR> 
<STRONG>Code of Practice for Businesses:</STRONG>


<P>

<B><BLOCKQUOTE>1. Recycle all your paper and cardboard.

<P>

2. Assess your current paper and cardboard program's effectiveness.

<P>

3. Recycle at least one other high volume material (other than paper or 
cardboard).

<P>

4. Buy recycled.
<P>

5. Reuse materials.

<P>

6. Reduce all types of garbage.</BLOCKQUOTE>

</B>

<P>Even if all you did was recycle all your paper and cardboard, this would 
help the cause in a major way.

<P>For more information or assistance with your business's recycling program call us at (604) 437-GVRD (4873), or email: <A HREF="mailto:webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca">webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca</A>

</TD>

</TR>

</TABLE>

