<HEAD>
<TITLE>Source Control
</TITLE>
</HEAD>


<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000>

<CENTER><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A>
</CENTER>

<H1>GVS&DD Source Control Program</H1>
<DL><DT>The following files are available electronically:<P>
<DD><A HREF="#download"><B>Sewer Use Bylaw No. 164</B></A><P>
<A HREF="#download"><B>Current Permit Holders</B></A><P>
<A HREF="#download"><B>Source Control Non-Compliance Lists</B></A></DL></DT>
<P>
<B>The Greater Vancouver Sewerage and Drainage District</B> (GVS&DD) Source Control 
Program regulates and controls waste discharges to the Districts sewerage and 
drainage system, at source.  Controlling discharges at source is key to 
prevention of high contaminant levels in the sewerage and drainage works which 
could compromise worker safety and health, interfere with the operation of the
collection system and treatment works, or pass through the system into the
environment without adequate treatment. <P>

In 1990, Sewer Use Bylaw No. 164 was adopted, providing the regulatory basis to
control non-domestic discharges to the District sewerage and drainage system.
Under the Bylaw, the District is empowered to impose requirements on the direct
or indirect discharge of non-domestic waste to District facilities.  Control of
non-domestic waste can take the form of prohibition of certain types of waste,
restrictions on contaminant concentrations, reductions in contaminant loadings,
and allocations of discharge volumes. The Bylaw is administered by the
District's Source Control group, except within the City of Vancouver boundaries,
where City of Vancouver staff handle this task. 
<P>
Administratively, control of non-domestic waste is accomplished through issue,
administration, and enforcement of authorizations, permits, and codes of practice.
Education and dissemination of information concerning the impact of waste
discharges are also important elements of the GVS&DD Source Control Program.   
<P>
The GVS&DD Source Control Group, currently consisting of ten staff,  was created
in 1990 to administer the Bylaw and develop and manage the Source Control Program
as part of the sewerage and drainage services provided by the District to its member
municipalities.  From 1990 to 1995 the primary focus of the Source Control Program
has been the implementation of the waste discharge permit system and the development
of administrative procedures for compliance monitoring and enforcement.
<P>
During 1994 and early 1995 an enforcement strategy was developed.  The strategy
is intended to improve compliance performance, while ensuring a fair,
consistent, and reasonable approach.  A key component of the enforcement
strategy is the Source Control Non-Compliance List, which is intended to
serve as a strong deterrent to non-compliance, and encourage industries
using the District's sewerage works to pro-actively manage their discharges
in accordance with the terms and conditions of their permits. The Non-Compliance
List is published twice per year, in March (covering July 1 to December 31)
and October (covering January 1 to June 30).
<P>
The emphasis of  the Source Control activity in 1996 is on:  improving
discharger compliance, developing better data management tools, increasing
regulatory activity in the commercial and institutional sector, and developing
cost recovery strategies.

<P>

<BR><ADDRESS>For more information on the GVS&DD Source Control Program, 
please contact
Grant McGillivray, Senior Officer, by E-mail at 
<A HREF="mailto:grant.mcgillivray@gvrd.bc.ca">grant.mcgillivray@gvrd.bc.ca</A></ADDRESS>
or by telephone at (604) 436-6723.


<P>
<A NAME="download"></A>
