<HEAD>



<TITLE>Air Quality FAQ</TITLE>



<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="GVRD">

</HEAD>



<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000>

<CENTER><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A>

</CENTER>



<H1>Air Quality FAQ</H1>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>(F</FONT>requently <FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>sked <FONT SIZE=+2>Q</FONT>uestions<FONT SIZE=+2>)</FONT>

<DL>

<DT><B>Can I burn today?  Is burning allowed? </B>

<DD>Residential burning is under municipal jurisdiction. In

most municipalities, backyard burning is prohibited. For those

that continue to permit burning, allowable burning periods are

restricted. Contact your municipality for further information.

<DT><B>Are people allowed to burn whatever they want in their

fireplaces?</B>

<DD>GVRD Air Pollution Control Bylaw No. 603 restricts the

burning of any fuels other than wood, paper (or derivatives of

these materials) or natural gas in domestic fireplaces.  Everyone

who lights a fire contributes to smoke-caused air pollution, so

we should make sure the combustion is efficient so that it releases

the least possible amount of smoke. Use seasoned, dry wood. Don't

burn treated or coated wood. Don't burn garbage such as plastics,

paper and cardboard. Reduce waste at source, avoid overpackaging.

Recycle whenever possible. Compost your yard leaves and clippings

rather than burning them. 



<DT><B>What can be done about smoking trucks, are they being tested?</B>

<DD>The provincial government will implement its heavy duty

vehicle testing program in 1996. Contact the Ministry of Environment,

Lands and Parks for further information.

<DT><B>How do I obtain Air Quality information?</B>

<DD>The Air Quality Index is available on this site at <A

HREF="/air/bro/aqindex.html">http://www.gvrd.bc.ca/air/bro/aqindex.html</A>

on the TV Weather Network and is published in the daily newspapers.

You can also call (604) 436-6767 or 1-800-665-1118.

<DT><B>Who do I contact to complain about air pollution problems?</B>



<DD>For air pollution inquiries or complaints call the GVRD

Air Quality Department at (604) 436-6777. Ministry of Environment:

(604) 582-5200.

<DT><B>I have to use my car to commute and don't have the option

of using public transit. What else can I do to reduce air pollution?</B>

</DT><UL>

<LI>Drive Wisely, Drive Less. Take transit, ride your bike,

or walk when possible. Combine several errands into one trip,

and carpool whenever possible. 

<LI>Reduce your driving speed.<B> </B> Driving at 80 km/hour

uses 15 -20 per cent less fuel than driving at 100 km/hour. 

<LI>Commute less and during off-peak hours.<B> </B>If possible,

take advantage of technology and work at home. Discuss the possibilities

with your employer. 

<LI>Save energy. Purchase a fuel efficient vehicle. They emit

fewer pollutants and save you money. At home keep your thermostat

at 20o C during the day and turn it down at night. Insulate your

home properly.

<LI>Don't overfill your gas tank. You will force out extra

emissions or you may spill gasoline which causes air pollution

when it evaporates. 

<LI>Test any used car at AirCare for emission problems before

 purchasing.  

<LI>Reduce the use of solvents, use water base paints and buy

non-aerosol products.

<LI>Use non-gasoline powered garden tools.

<LI>Plant trees and low maintenance landscaping plants.

<LI>Educate yourself and your community about air quality.

<LI>Contact the Communications and Education department at (604)

432-6339 to obtain print materials or to book free workshops on

Air Quality issues.

</UL>

<HR>

