<HEAD>

<TITLE>Waste Reduction and Recycling FAQ</TITLE>

<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="gvrd">
</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000>
<CENTER><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A>
</CENTER>

<H1>Waste Reduction and Recycling FAQ</H1>
<P>
<FONT SIZE=+2>(F</FONT>requently <FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>sked <FONT SIZE=+2>Q</FONT>uestions<FONT SIZE=+2>)</FONT>
<DL>
<DT><B>Where can I find information on Recycling Companies in
the GVRD, particularly paper recyclers. </B>
<DD>Please contact the Recycling Hotline at (604) 732-9253 or 1-800-667-4321.
<DT><B>Where do I get a blue-box or recycling container? </B>
<DD>Through your municipality - the phone numbers are in the blue
pages of the BC Tel Directory.
<DT><B>Why hasn't my garbage been picked up? </B>
<DD>Check with your municipality - the phone numbers are in the
blue pages of the BC Tel Directory.
<DT><B>Where/how do I get rid of my old refrigerator? </B>
<DD>If it is in working condition B.C. Hydro will pick up, if
not call the Recycling Hot Line at (604) 732-9253 or toll free
1-800-667-4321 Monday to Friday - 9 a.m. to 4 p.m.
<DT><B>How do I get rid of drywall? </B>
<UL>
<LI>New West Gypsum at (604) 534-9925
<LI>North Shore Transfer Station at (604) 929-5471
<LI>Matsqui Transfer Station at (604) 853-0508
<LI>Maple Ridge Residential Transfer Station at (604) 466-9277
<LI>Langley Residential Transfer Station at (604) 856-3020
<LI>Coquitlam Resource Recovery Plant at (604) 521-1715.
</UL>

<DT><B>How do I get rid of or recycle paint, household hazardous
wastes (HHW), old pesticides and solvents, etc.?</B>
<DD>Paint drop-off depots or depots operated by the Paint Care
Association (604) 482-8686 or Home Hardware. Please phone ahead.
Paint Care Hotline, toll free 1-800-505-0139.
<DD>HHW, old pesticides, solvents, etc.: try to use up or give
away to be used, if not then store in a safe place until facilities
are in place.


<DT><B>How do I recycle household batteries and fluorescent light
bulbs? </B>
<DD>Button batteries may be returned to jewellery, camera and electronics stores.
Currently only three areas have recycling programs for household and industrial
batteries, these are: 
<DD>District of Burnaby - call their Environmental Health Division at 
(604) 294-7390.
<DD>Township of Langley - call their Engineering Department at (604) 533-6006. 
<DD>City of Langley at (604) 530-3131.
<DD>Barring any of the above, mercury reduced, normal alkaline batteries may be 
thrown into the regular garbage.
<DD>Fluorescent lamps contain mercury and care should be taken not to break them: Nu
Life Industries Inc. of Aldergrove, B.C. (604) 857-5588 or toll free 1-800-247-6724 is a
licensed recycler of fluorescent lamps and dry cell batteries in British Columbia.


<DT><B>What is a Transfer Station? </B>
<DD>A transfer station reduces the volume of traffic necessary
for transporting residential and commercial waste away from the
municipalities. Waste is received from communities that are within
close proximity to the transfer station and screened for recyclable
material. The recyclable material is collected and sold to various
industries, wherever possible hazardous and problem wastes are
removed. The remaining residue is then compacted and hauled away
to an incinerator or landfill in larger transport vehicles. This
process provides both environmental and economical benefits to
the Greater Vancouver area.
<DT><B>Where does my garbage go? </B>
<DD>One of four disposal sites - Vancouver Landfill, Port Mann
Landfill, Cache Creek Landfill or the Burnaby Incinerator.
<DT><B>Why haul waste to Cache Creek Landfill? </B>
<DD>It is dry. In areas of high rainfall, like the Lower Mainland,
landfills tend to generate large quantities of leachate (a polluting
liquid that can seep into groundwater) and landfill gas (an odorous
gas made up mostly of carbon dioxide and methane). The Cache Creek
area is arid - producing minimal leachate and landfill gas - and
is an ideal location for a landfill.
<DD>The project included an agreement with another company to
construct a wood chip facility in Cache Creek. When refuse trailers
haul GVRD garbage to Cache Creek, the same trailers haul wood
chips back to the Lower Mainland. The landfill and chip plant
have generated 70 full-time and 10 part-time jobs in the Cache
Creek/Ashcroft area.
<DT><B>Where do I dispose of my garbage and how much does it cost?
</B>
<DD>The facilities are listed below and the cost is $69/tonne. The cost will be reduced
to $64/tonne effective July 1, 1996.
</DL>

<P>
<U><B>SOLID WASTE FACILITIES</B></U>
