<HTML>



<HEAD>



<TITLE>Strategic Planning FAQ</TITLE>



<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="gvrd">

<META NAME="OPERATOR" CONTENT="gvrd">

</HEAD>



<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000>

<CENTER><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A>

</CENTER>

<H1>Strategic Planning FAQ</H1>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>(F</FONT>requently <FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>sked <FONT SIZE=+2>Q</FONT>uestions<FONT SIZE=+2>)</FONT>

<DL>



<DT><B>When is the government going to provide alternative transportation

choices so that I can leave my car at home?</B>

<DD>While public transit is a provincial responsibility the GVRD

has been working in partnership with the government to develop

land use and transportation planning that will reduce dependence

on the private automobile. The Province recently announced its

10-year transit development plan which includes two rapid transit

lines and fast bus service. Work has already started on developing

the light rail and rapid bus facilities in the Broadway-Lougheed-Coquitlam-New

Westminster corridor and rapid bus in the Richmond corridor will

be one of the first improvements to be implemented. 

<DD>For more information about Transport 2021 Medium and Long

Range Transportation Plans contact the GVRD Strategic Planning

Department at  (604) 432-6375.

<DT><B>How fast is our population increasing?</B>

<DD>Every year, the region grows by 40,000 new residents. That

is enough to populate a city the size of New Westminster every

year. 

<DT><B>How does our growth compare to other parts of North America?</B>

<DD>Greater Vancouver is one of the top ten fastest growing metropolitan

areas in North America.

<DT><B>Where is the growth coming from?</B>

<DD>Studies show about one-third of the region's population growth

comes from people who already live here - the natural birth rate.

One-third comes from people moving here from other Canadian provinces

and territories, and one-third comes from immigration.

<DT><B>What are the benefits of implementing a regional growth

strategy?</B>

<DD>By managing growth efficiently through the <I>Livable Region

Strategic Plan</I>, air emissions will be reduced by one-third,

$2.2 billion in transportation capital spending will be saved,

and land, equivalent in size to the City of Vancouver, will be

protected from development within the <I>Green Zone</I> .

<DT><B>What is the population of the GVRD?</B>

<DD>In 1995 it was 1,819,533

<DT><B>What is the land area of GVRD?</B>

<DD>290,462.8  (hectares)

<DT><B>How will the Green Zone be protected from development?</B>

<DD>The Green Zone comprises lands owned and regulated by many

different agencies. The watershed and parks are publicly owned

and have been reserved for non-urban uses.  The Agricultural Land

Reserve (ALR) is largely privately-owned, but development within

the ALR is controlled by the regulations of the B.C. Agricultural

Land Commission, which restricts non-farm development within the

ALR. Ecological habit is protected by federal and provincial agencies.

Hazardous lands, like steep slopes along stream courses are protected

by municipal Official Community Plan and zoning bylaws. In short,

the protection of the Green Zone is a true partnership involving

local, regional, provincial and federal governments and their

agencies.

<DT><B>How does the Livable Region Strategic Plan affect downtown

Vancouver?</B>

<DD>The Plan recognizes downtown Vancouver as the primary business

centre in the region. Downtown associations are concerned about

the continued vitality of the downtown, especially in response

to the decentralization of some downtown services to the suburban

communities around the City of Vancouver.  Rather than have decentralization

spread across the region, the Livable Region Strategic Plan proposes

that, to the extent that decentralization occurs through market

trends, decentralized development should be centralized in one

of eight suburban regional centres.  Concentrating non-downtown

commercial growth in these Regional Town Centres (RTCs) helps

support the public investment facilities like rail transit and

the SeaBus.  The idea behind RTCs is to complement downtown Vancouver,

not to compete with it. The growth of housing on the downtown

peninsula, and the increase in transit accessibility to downtown

Vancouver, both help reinforce the downtown as the core of the

metropolitan region.

<DT><B>Why is it necessary to have more complete communities?</B>

<DD>When the GVRD surveyed Greater Vancouver residents, 91 per

cent said they would prefer to live and work within the same community.

 Unfortunately, this is not always possible today, because there

are some communities where there are fewer jobs in the community

than there are workers. As a consequence, these workers are forced

to commute to jobs in other communities. By pursuing a development

form that produces communities where jobs and services are close

to households, the need to travel long distances across the region

through several municipalities can be minimized. When residents

can make shorter trips, they are more likely to walk or cycle,

as opposed to driving a motor vehicle.

</UL>



<HR>

