<HTML>



<HEAD>



<TITLE>Drinking Water FAQ</TITLE>



<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="GVRD">

<META NAME="GENERATOR" CONTENT="Internet Assistant for Microsoft Word 2.0 beta 1">

</HEAD>

<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000>



<P>

<CENTER><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A>

</CENTER>

<H1>Drinking Water FAQ</H1>



<P>

<FONT SIZE=5>(F</FONT>requently <FONT SIZE=5>A</FONT>sked <FONT SIZE=5>Q</FONT>uestions<FONT SIZE=5>)</FONT>

<DL>

<DT>How much water is used per person, per day in the GVRD?

<DD>About 650 litres per person, per day. That includes water

used by people at home, and the water used by industries, businesses

and institutions in the GVRD.

<DT>What is the green/blue staining on bathroom fixtures, clothes

and hair?

<DD>The source of the green or blue stains is copper which is

leached from copper piping by our naturally acidic water. The

problem is most noticeable in the hot water recirculating loops

in high-rise buildings. Use a detergent (such as Tide) for laundry

as anything made of pure soap (such as Ivory Snow) will make the

staining worse as the soap precipitates the copper out of the

water. As part of the Drinking Water Treatment Program, the GVRD

hopes to implement pH and alkalinity adjustment (corrosion control)

by 1998 which will substantially reduce this problem.

<DT>How much Fluoride is in the water and do we add any?

<DD>Fluoride is not added to the water source, and the natural

level is less than 0.05 mg/L. Contact your dentist if you&iacute;re

interested in fluoride drops.

<DT>Why are my water rates so high?

<DD>Each municipality is different. The GVRD charges a wholesale

rate to each member municipality and they are individual retailers:

rates are set by the municipality. In general, residential water

rates are among the lowest in North America.

<DT>Why is our tap water cloudy?

<DD>A major source of turbidity or cloudy water is sediment that

finds its way into the water system. This is noticeable during

periods of heavy, sustained rainfall when the forces of erosion

are at a maximum in the watersheds. Also our water is very soft

and corrosion occurs within the water distribution system. Corrosion

products (such as rust) can also discolour the water.

<DT>

<DD>There are a number of conditions which can result in local

turbidity upsets including construction or pipes being changed,

high flows due to a fire or a flusher truck filling, or high flows

due to hot weather. In general, anything that may change the flow

of water and cause it to sweep particles into the water current

may result in cloudy/coloured water. Unless there is a general

problem with cloudy water, flush the tap to clear up the problem.

If this does not work, contact your municipality to flush the

main(s) feeding the residence in question.

<DT>Why is there no backup plan when the water is cloudy?

<DD>There is a plan - the Westerly Transfer when completed in

1998 will enable us to remove either the Capilano or Seymour source

( these sources have the worst histories of turbidity) from service

and supply more of the distribution system with Coquitlam water,

which is usually unaffected by turbidity events. Future implementation

of filtration for the Seymour and Capilano sources will enable

the GVRD to supply clean, clear water from these two sources,

even during the heavy fall/winter rain season.

<DT>When will water metering start? Why not now?

<DD>There are studies currently underway. It is not feasible to

implement now due to the cost which is more than $100 million.

This is a major reason for having summer sprinkling restrictions

in place, to delay the need for water metering.

<DT>Why do we have sprinkling restrictions when we have so much

water?

<DD>Several reasons: growing population; limited storage capacity;

restrictions are very minimal and are a precautionary measure

to avoid more stringent restrictions or a total ban. They help

keep the cost of water supply down.

<DT>When are the sprinkling restrictions?

</DL>



<UL>

<LI><B>June 1 - September 30</B>

<LI><B>4 a.m. - 9 a.m. &amp; 7 p.m. - 10 p.m.</B>

<LI><B>EVEN numbered addresses - Wednesday &amp; Saturday</B>

<LI><B>ODD numbered addresses - Thursday &amp; Sunday</B>

<LI><B>Can we use the sprinkler on our vegetable/flower gardens?

</B>

</UL>



<DL>

<DT>

<DD>Under normal sprinkling restrictions, only lawns are affected

and you may use a sprinkler for watering vegetables, shrubs and

flowers. If conditions become more severe, then the GVRD and your

municipality will ask that you water your flowers, vegetables,

shrubs, etc. with a hand-held hose, with a spring loaded trigger

nozzle. There is no restriction on the times for this purpose,

but the best time to water your garden is first thing in the morning,

before the sun has become too hot.

<DT>What address do we go by in a townhouse complex or trailer

park?

<DD>The actual street address should be used to determine which

days for sprinkling, NOT the unit number.

<DT>Can the sprinkler be used by children to play?

<DD>Technically, this is against the restrictions, unless it is

during your allotted hours for sprinkling, however, children's

water toys are allowed within reason.

<DT>How can I possibly water my apartment building complex within

so few hours?

<DD>This is a question for the individual municipalities (listed

in the blue pages at the back of your telephone book). Some municipalities

will provide written exemptions in these cases.

<DT>How hard is my water?

<DD>The water is very soft because it is a surface water which

means it does not pick up minerals from the soil. The hardness

of the water is in the area of 5 milligrams per litre (ppm) which

is less than half a grain.

<DT>Why does my water taste and smell like chlorine?

<DD>The GVRD is required by the BC Safe Drinking Water Regulation

to disinfect the drinking water for health and safety reasons.

At present, we chlorinate at the source to secure a residual of

0.9 mg/L free chlorine after 10 minutes contact time.

<DT>

<DD>Occasionally, (most commonly during the late summer/early

fall or during the winter when the lakes are covered with ice)

low levels of ammonia arising from natural processes can be found

in the water. The ammonia combines with chlorine to produce chloramines

which have a very chlorinous taste and odour. This is not harmful

but can be very displeasing. The problem dissipates once sustained

rainfall or spring snowmelt occurs which results in a good exchange

of water through the lake.

<DT>Where can I get my water tested?

<DD>GVRD water is tested daily for microbiological and chemical/physical

characteristics. If you want your water tested, the GVRD does

not analyse water from private residences unless requested to

do so by the municipality or health department of the residence

in question. If you feel the water is unsafe to drink and are

concerned about your health, call your local health unit.

</DL>



<P>

<FONT SIZE=2></FONT>

<UL>

<LI>Simon Fraser Health Unit - (604) 927-2000

<LI>North Shore Health Department - (604) 983-6839

<LI>Burnaby Health Department - (604) 294-7260

<LI>Vancouver Health Department - (604) 736-2033

<LI>Richmond Health Unit - (604) 276-4050

<LI>Boundary Health Unit -(604) 594-0441

</UL>



<DL>

<DT>Where can I get water, other than GVRD water, tested?

<DD>We cannot recommend private labs but look up labs under &quot;analytical

laboratories&quot; in the yellow pages. Also, the health unit

in the area in question will provide free bacteriological analyses

where health concerns exist or drinking water quality is in question.

Contact your local health unit. 

</DL>



<P>

<FONT SIZE=2></FONT>

<HR>



