<HEAD>



<TITLE>Wastewater System FAQ</TITLE>



<META NAME="AUTHOR" CONTENT="gvrd">

</HEAD>



<BODY bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000>

<CENTER><A HREF="/index.html"><IMG SRC="/go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A>

</CENTER>



<H1>Wastewater System FAQ</H1>

<P>

<FONT SIZE=+2>(F</FONT>requently <FONT SIZE=+2>A</FONT>sked <FONT SIZE=+2>Q</FONT>uestions<FONT SIZE=+2>)</FONT>

<DL>

<DT><B>What does the Sewerage &amp; Drainage department do?</B>

<DD>Our core business is the collection and treatment of the wastewater

generated by 17 member municipalities in the Greater Vancouver

Regional District.

<DT><B>When I flush the toilet or have a shower, where does my

wastewater go?</B>

<DD>After leaving your home, it flows into your municipal sewer

system which connects to one of the regional sewer collection

systems.

<DD>The GVRD is divided into four sewerage areas: Vancouver, Lulu

Island, Fraser and North Shore. The wastewater from the three

North Shore municipalities goes to the Lions Gate Wastewater Treatment

Plant; from Vancouver, part of Burnaby, University Endowment Lands,

and Sea Island in Richmond it goes to the Iona Island Wastewater

Treatment plant; from Richmond it goes to Lulu Island Wastewater

Treatment plant; and the wastewater from the remaining municipalities

such as Delta, Surrey, most of Burnaby, Port Moody, Coquitlam,

Port Coquitlam, Langley township and district, Pitt Meadows and

Maple Ridge goes to the Annacis Island Wastewater Treatment plant.

The wastewater from the Walnut Grove area in the Township of Langley

is treated at the Northwest Langley secondary treatment plant.

<DT><B>What happens to the wastewater at the treatment plant?</B>

<DD>With the exception of the Northwest Langley plant which is

a secondary plant, the Region's wastewater goes through a primary

treatment process after which it is discharged through outfalls

into the receiving waters. The Lions Gate plant discharges into

Burrard Inlet, the Iona Plant into Georgia Strait, and Lulu, Northwest

Langley and Annacis discharge into the Fraser River. Currently

the Lulu Island and Annacis plants are being upgraded to provide

secondary treatment, scheduled for completion by the end of 1998.

<DT><B>How can I get a tour of a treatment plant?</B>

<DD>Contact the GVRD's Communications &amp; Education department

(604) 432-6339.

<DT><B>Is it safe to dump paint and other chemicals into the drain

or flush them down the toilet?</B>

<DD>No, it is harmful to the wastewater treatment process and

the environment. Please call the GVRD's recycling hot line, (604)732-9253

or 1-800-667-4321 for disposal information.

<DT><B>What are Combined Sewer Overflows?</B>

<DD>In some of the Region's older wastewater piping systems, in

Vancouver, Burnaby and New Westminster, both human sewage and

rainfall runoff were put into the same pipes. However, when it

rains hard there is not enough room in the pipes to carry the

combined flow and the system has to relieve itself by overflowing

untreated wastewater into pipes that discharge directly into the

receiving waters. Sometimes the flows in combined systems are

so large that the wastewater comes out of residential and business

plumbing.

<DT><B>Who should I contact when my storm sewer or, in the case

of a combined system, the combined sewer overflows into my residence

or business?</B>

<DD>In most cases you are connected to a sewer owned by the municipality

in which you live so you should call your city hall and not the

GVRD's Sewerage &amp; Drainage Department.

<DT><B>What is Nutrifor&#153;?</B>

<DD>Nutrifor is the trademark name the GVRD has registered for

its biosolids products.

<DT><B>What are biosolids?</B>

<DD>Biosolids are produced at wastewater treatment plants from

the organic material removed during the sewage treatment process.

Biosolids can be recycled as an organic fertilizer and soil amendment.

<DT><B>Are there any heavy metals in biosolids?</B>

<DD>The GVRD source control program is very effective at removing

heavy metals from industry before they enter the sewage system.

GVRD biosolids meet agriculture standards for low heavy metals

and are routinely tested to meet these stringent standards.

<DT><B>What about bugs in biosolids?</B>

<DD>Nasty bugs, pathogens and viruses, are killed by the digestion

process at the wastewater treatment plants. Mesophilic digesters

kill 99.9 per cent of all these bad bugs. Quality control laboratories

ensure the biosolids are safe for recycling.

<DT><B>What about other toxic materials?</B>

<DD>Although we are not a very industrialized region, the GVRD

monitors all kinds of other toxic products, (including PAH's,

PCB, dioxins, furans, etc.) to ensure they are not present in

wastewater or biosolids in significant quantities. Our biosolids

do not contain toxic materials at concentrations higher than normally

found in the environment.

<DT><B>What do we do with our biosolids?</B>

<DD>The Nutrifor program recycles all of the biosolids we produce.

Nutrifor has been used to grow trees faster, produce top soil

for highway projects, fertilize farmland, reclaim mine waste rock

piles and tailings ponds, recover old landfills and prevent soil

erosion in parks.

<DT><B>How are biosolids produced?</B>

<DD>Although there are a number of different processes to make

biosolids the GVRD collects sewage sludge at wastewater treatment

facilities, digests (a microbiological and heat treatment process)

the sludge then dewaters it to produce biosolids for recycling.

<DT><B>How can I find out more about biosolids and Nutrifor?</B>

<DD>The Nutrifor hot line to the GVRD Residuals Management is

(604) 451-6185. E-mail can be sent to nutrifor@gvrd.bc.ca

</DL>



<P>

