<PRE>





















</PRE>
<H2><A NAME="overview">Overview</A></H2>
<P>In British Columbia, we are blessed with an abundance of natural resources, 
including clean air. In the Lower Fraser Valley, where 54 per cent of the province's 
population lives, clean air is a major concern of residents and vistors. Most of
the  year, regional air quality is good. It easily meets federal objectives that have 
been established to regulate levels of air pollutants. However, at certain times 
of the year, usually in the late spring and summer, our air quality can deteriorate 
to unacceptable levels. Occasionally, the air quality problem in Lower Fraser Valley 
is one of the most serious in Canada.


<P><STRONG>Strategy</STRONG>
<BR>Coordinating air quality efforts with both the federal and provincial 
governments, and at the same time, preserving air quality without unduly 
stifling economic activity, is a challenging task, one the GVRD's 
<A HREF="../../air/bro/aqmp.html">Air Quality Management 
Plan</A> (AQMP) adopted in December, 1994 attempts to address.

<P><STRONG>Monitoring</STRONG>
<BR>Having accurate air quality measurements is an essential part of the
solution to the air quality problem. The GVRD operates one of the most 
extensive ambient <A HREF="../../air/bro/aqmeasu.html">air
quality monitoring</A>  networks in North America.  This network has provided much of the data used to identify the 
air quality issues and <A HREF="../../air/bro/aqprior.html">priorities</A>  
in the GVRD.

<P><STRONG>Sources & Solutions</STRONG>
<BR>Air pollution is a difficult problem to control. There are many 
different <A HREF="../../air/bro/aqsourc.html">sources of
emissions</A>, spread over a wide area. Large-scale  industrial operations, commercial facilities such as dry cleaners and 
gas stations, home furnaces,  fireplaces, cars,  trucks, buses - all 
contribute to air pollution. There is no one single solution to the 
problem. In fact, there are as many <A
HREF="../../air/bro/aqsolut.html">solutions  to the problem</A> as there are sources.

<P><STRONG>What Next?</STRONG>
<BR>What does the future hold for air quality in the Fraser Valley? 
What are the <A HREF="../../air/bro/aqnext.html">next
steps</A> that GVRD plans to implement in the next ten  years and beyond? In 
<A HREF="../../air/bro/aqualit.html">conclusion</A> is
this the right time for addressing  this problem or is it too late
to make a  difference? What can <A HREF="../../air/bro/aqyou.html">you</A> do to help?

<HR>
