<PRE>



















</PRE>
<P><H2><A NAME="Overview">Overview</A></H2>
<STRONG>Just how wasteful are we?</STRONG><BR>
 <IMG SRC="../medarch/waste/van_dump.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT VSPACE=15
HSPACE=15 ALT="Image of B.C. Place overflowing with garbage">
Every man, woman and child in Canada produces 1.7 kg of waste per capita per 
day. That's more than Americans or Australians, more than Europeans, almost
twice as  much as people in Japan and Sweden, and more than three times as much as the 
people in China.
<P>
In 1989, over 1.2 million tonnes of municipal waste was produced in the Greater 
Vancouver Regional District-enough to fill B.C. Place Stadium to overflowing! 
This will increase to 1.6 million tonnes by the year 2000, unless
something is done to prevent it.

<P>
<STRONG>A Time for Change</STRONG><BR>
The year 2000 is a target date set by the federal and provincial governments for a 
50 per cent reduction of waste disposal. In order to accomplish
this goal, we must  practise the 3Rs- Reduce, Reuse and Recycle. 
<P>

<STRONG>Reduce, Reuse, Recycle</STRONG><BR>
First of all, we must reduce the amount of garbage
we produce. We can do this by  practising selective shopping. We can cut out buying
unnecessary products; we  can cut down on excess packaging.
<P>
Secondly, we must reuse products. This means
where possible we must purchase  non-disposable and reusable items. We must also consider repairing what we 
already have instead of throwing it out.
<P>
Finally, we must recycle part of the waste we
generate. Traditionally, we  have viewed waste as garbage and not as
a resource.  With programs for the 
collection, processing and marketing of recyclables, we 
have the opportunity to divert much of our garbage. Materials such
as newspaper,  glass, metal and plastic can be reused to manufacture new products.
<P>
We must respond to the challenge by changing our <A
HREF="../../waste/bro/swici.html">industrial and 
commercial</A> practices, our <A HREF="../../waste/bro/swreduc.html">household</A> 
habits and, most importantly, our attitudes.

<HR>
