<HTML>

<HEAD>
<TITLE>Water our most precious resource
</TITLE>
</HEAD><body bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000>

<CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A></CENTER>

<A NAME="toptop"></A>

<CENTER><H2>WATER</H2></CENTER>
<CENTER><P><H3>Protecting a Precious Resource.<BR>
Raise your glass to our water system.</H3></P></CENTER>
<P>As a community we tend to take the provision of quality drinking water for granted. 
We turn on the tap at home or work or at a drinking fountain in the park and the water is there. 
We don't think much about how it got to us.</P>

<IMG  SRC="../medarch/water/lgwat.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT HSPACE=80>

<A NAME="menu"> </A>
<H3>Greater Vancouver Water System</H3>
<UL>
<LI><A HREF="/water/bro/waterfaq.html">Frequently Asked Questions about our drinking water</A>
<LI><A HREF="#dam">Where water comes from</A>
<LI><A HREF="../../water/bro/wathis.html">History</A>
<LI><A HREF="../../water/bro/watcon.html">Using water efficiently</A>
<LI><A HREF="../../water/bro/wathel.html">Protecting your health</A>
<LI><A HREF="../../water/bro/watman.html">Watershed management</A>
<LI><A HREF="#cd">CD ROM Information through technology</A>
<LI><A HREF="../../water/pr/wapr01.html">The facts on Cryptosporidium</A>
<LI><A HREF="/go/arch/newsrel.html">News Release Archives</A>
</UL>
<P><STRONG>Nature's Perfect Diet Drink</STRONG></P>
<P>It's fat-free, cholesterol-free and calorie-free. It's also essential to good health,
it tastes great and it's cheap.</P>

What $1 will buy:
<UL>
	<LI>Less than two litres of gasoline
	<LI>Less than one litre of milk
	<LI>Less than one litre of soft drink
	<LI>Over 10,000 litres of mountain-fresh water from the GVRD system,
	based on the rate at which it is sold to member municipalities.
</UL>
	<STRONG>It's a real bargain.</STRONG>

<P><A NAME="dam"><STRONG>Where water comes from</STRONG> </A></P>
<P>Few of us give more than a passing thought to where our water comes from. 
Like magic, we turn on the tap countless times each day and out pours some of the
best quality drinking water of any large urban area in the world.</P>


<P>A raindrop's journey from cloud to tap is a long and complex one. By the time a
raindrop becomes one of millions to pour from your tap, it has spent more than half its 
life cycle travelling through one of Greater Vancouver's three watersheds.</P>

<P><A HREF="../../water/bro/watman.html">The Greater Vancouver Watersheds</A> are mountainous areas where the snowmelt, creeks
and streams flow to the valley bottom to three large supply lakes. Our watersheds are
within the mountains on the North Shore and north of Coquitlam.</P>

<A NAME="1dam"></A>
<P>The three mountainous watersheds - <A HREF="../../water/bro/watman.html">Capilano, Seymour and Coquitlam</A> - are protected
lands collecting and holding water for 1.8 million people. The three watersheds cover
58,500 hectares, an area the size of about 145 Stanley Parks.</P>

<P>Access to the watersheds is limited to protect the region's water supply from
human contamination. Partly because of this, a degree of mystery has evolved around
the vast tracts of forested mountains. Increasingly, people want to know where the
watersheds are, how big they are, how they function and how they are being managed.</P> 

<P>This document is intended to provide background information on the GVRD's three watersheds,
describing their key role in the overall water supply system, as well as the 
management challenges they present.</P>
<CENTER>
<A HREF="../../water/bro/wathis.html"><IMG ALIGN=bottom SRC="../../water/av_media/1900.gif"><BR>
Let the men from the 1900s take you back in time</A> </CENTER>
<H4>History</H4>
<P>The watersheds, as we know them today, have changed much in form and character since the
movement of ancient glaciers molded the valleys that are now such an integral part of our 
water system. Over the last 100 years humans have also left their imprint.</P>

<STRONG>Protecting your health</STRONG>
<P>The GVRD takes samples from the rivers and reservoirs of each watershed to monitor bacteria
and other characteristics. Most samples are tested in the GVRD laboratory.
In addition, hydrological monitoring is helping the GVRD to maintain a <A HREF="../../water/bro/wathel.html">high quality water supply</A>,
and to build a better understanding of the natural processes in each watershed that can affect drinking water
quality such as erosion, wildlife, forest health and the effects of forest fires.</P>

<A HREF="#top">Top of page</A>


<H4>Watershed Management</H4>
<P>The Regional District's <A HREF="../../water/bro/watman.html">watershed management</A> 
program is designed to minimize the effects of slides, soil erosion and wildfires on our drinking water quality, 
should they occur.

<P>The three watersheds are characterized by steep terrain and heavy rainfall. With protection and maintenance
of water quality as the sole objective, watershed management activities are designed to protect
against large scale and potentially damaging natural occurrences. In  this context, a range of water
quality improvement projects is undertaken including stream clearing, stream bank stabilization, removal
of fire prone trees, silviculture, <A HREF="../../water/bro/watman.html#monitoring">hydrologic monitoring,</A> forest research, 
<A HREF="../../water/bro/watman.html#fire">fire protection</A> and <A HREF="../../water/bro/watman.html#road">maintenance</A>
of access roads.</P>

<A NAME="cd"></A>
<H4>CD ROM Information through technology</A></H4>
<IMG ALIGN=top SRC="../medarch/water/cdrom.gif" ALT= "CD rom shot"><P>
	<P>The GVRD is moving into science and technology in a big way.  
	Computer buffs and amateurs alike will have a chance to play a new interactive 
	computer simulation program that challenges players to see how lifestyle choices 
	today will affect the world 30 years from now.</P>

<P>Complete with full colour,  sound effects, and music, <A HREF="../../info/bro/cdrom.html">"Creating Our Future"</A> 
allows players to make environmental decisions while moving through a simulated 3D home.  
Players learn about environmental issues and initiatives through simple choices such as 
whether to take a bath or shower.</P>

<P>The CD ROM program was developed by the GVRD in conjunction with Science World, the 
BC Ministry of Environment, Lands and Parks, and Go Green. It is a permanent
exhibit at Science World and is available on both Mac and IBM-compatible CD ROM
discs. Interactive simulations on waste reduction and air quality are
available to complement the one on drinking water and wastewater.
Visit Science World and try your hand at "Creating Our Future." 
Copies of the CD ROM "Creating Our Future" are available through Science World for $25 CDN or $20 
US, plus shipping and handling. <STRONG>Call <A HREF="http://www.scienceworld.bc.ca">Science World</A> 
at (604)443-7500.</STRONG>
<P><A HREF="water.html#top">Top of page</A>

<HR>
