<TITLE>The Nature Legacy and GVRD Parks</TITLE>

</HEAD>
	
<body bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000>
<CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG
SRC="../../go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A></CENTER>
	
<CENTER>
<H1>The Nature Legacy and Regional Parks</H1>
<P>
Vancouver's world-famous Stanley Park is a precious gem. A pearl.
<P>
With the recent addition of lands from the Lower Mainland Nature<BR>

Legacy the GVRD's parks system has grown in size to the equivalent of<BR>

28 Stanley Parks. A string of pearls adorning The Livable Region. </P><BR>

<A HREF="../medarch/todo/trees.jpeg"><IMG SRC="../medarch/todo/trees2.gif"
WIDTH=186 HIGHT=124 ALT="[Photo looking up at tall trees]"></A>
<P>
Over time, some treasures diminish. Not these. <BR>
<P>
Their wonder will last forever.
<P>
<H2> Greater Vancouver the Big Winner<BR>
in Nature Legacy Program</H2> </CENTER>
<P> 
GVRD residents already proud of their spectacular outdoor setting have even more
reason to rejoice. As of June, their amount of dedicated parkland almost quadrupled,
from about 21,000 hectares to more than 80,000 hectares.
<P>
<A HREF="../medarch/todo/sumas.jpeg"><IMG SRC="
../medarch/todo/sumas.gif"VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=RIGHT ALT="[Photo of Sumas
Mnt.]"> </A>
<P>In addition to the creation of two new large provincial parks in the
Indian Arm and Pinecone-Burke Mountain areas, new regional parkland secures key
pieces of the GVRD'S Green Zone, a critical building block of its Livable Region
Strategic Plan.
<P> 
One thousand, eight hundred and ninety-two hectares, including five new regional
parks, and extensions to six existing parks, brings the total size of the impressive
GVRD park system to  11,320 hectares spread among 25 parks.
<P>
<A HREF="../medarch/todo/sumas1.jpeg"><IMG SRC="../medarch/todo/sumas1.gif" VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT 
ALT="[Photo of Sumas Mnt.]"></A>
<P>
The new parkland is part of the $71.4 million Lower Mainland Nature
Legacy, a program financed by the Province of B.C., GVRD, the Federal Government and
several municipalities.
<P> 
There are many benefits to GVRD residents. New parkland has been secured in high
growth areas so that
Increasing recreation demands can be better met. Public access to waterfronts can be
improved, and threatened regional features and habitats conserved.
<P> <A HREF="../medarch/todo/pineco.jpeg"><IMG SRC="
../medarch/todo/pineco.gif" VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=RIGHT ALT="[Photo of 
Burke Mountain]"></A>  
In 1994, the GVRD created the Heritage Parkland Acquisition Fund in response to
strong public support for acquiring and protecting regional wildlife and recreation
lands while affordable and still available. When the Province of B.C. initiated
Nature Legacy discussions, GVRD was ready, willing and able to join in and help
determine which critical parkland sites should be purchased.
<P> 
The properties were acquired through contributions of land and money from the
Province of B.C. (49,150 hectares), Delta, Surrey. Port Coquitlam, Coquitlam, Langley
Township, and Environment Canada. GVRD contributed $12.8 million, and also
transferred its lands at Granite Falls Regional Park to the new provincial park in
Indian Arm.
<P><A HREF="../medarch/todo/parkmap.jpeg"><IMG SRC="
../medarch/todo/parkmap.gif" VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=LEFT ALT="[Photo of 
Nature Legacy Map]"></A> 
In addition, two major land gifts each worth $1 million - one at lona Beach
and one on Douglas Island - were received from Canadian Forest products.
<P>
A look at the map tells the story: from Richmond to Abbotsford, from Belcarra to
Delta, the new sites go a long way to enhancing our recreational opportunities
protecting wildlife and creating a heritage waterway.
<P>  <A HREF="../medarch/todo/pineco2.jpeg"><IMG SRC="
../medarch/todo/pineco2.gif" VSPACE=10 HSPACE=10 ALIGN=RIGHT ALT="[Photo of 
Pinecone Lake]"></A> 
The Fraser River component of the Nature Legacy is particularly impressive. Lands
were acquired at Surrey Bend, Douglas Island, Barnston Island, Don and Lion Islands,
Poplar Island, Brae Island, and Colony Farm. New lands were added to Derby Reach,
Glen Valley and lona Beach.
<P> 
Combined with provincial wildlife reserves along the Fraser, there will now be more
than 80 kilometres of riverfront for residents to explore!

