Surrey owns and operates the Port Mann Landfill and receives a similar financial benefit.<P>Under Water:<BR>-	West Vancouver obtains some of its water supply from Eagle Lake, which is under its jurisdiction. <HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#inc">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="inc">$16 Increase for the Average Homeowner</A>  </H3><P> The 1995 final budget for the Greater Vancouver Regional District is $319.8 million, a reduction of  $3.8 million from the provisional budget adopted by the Board of Directors in December. The final  budget is up 4.5 per cent over last year.<P>While the impact will vary from municipality to municipality the average homeowner will pay $16 more in GVRD taxes this year. Total Regional District taxes on an average home will be $291. The figure is based on a house with a 1995 assessed value of $288,000. If your assessment is higher you will in most instances pay more than this, if your assessment is lower you will in most instances pay less.<P>There are about 460,000 owners of single family homes, condos, townhouses, and duplexes in Greater Vancouver.<P>Of the $16 increase, $9 will go to the regional water system, $5 to the sewerage system, $1 to solid waste management programs, and $1 to hospital capital programs (construction and equipment). <P>The budget covers all GVRD functions including water supply, sewers, hospital construction and equipment, solid waste management, regional parks, air quality control, strategic planning, labour relations, and the 9-1-1- emergency phone service.<HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#dol">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="dol">1995 GVRD Tax Dollar</A> </H3><H4>Where It Goes</H4> <PRE>Hospital construction/equipment					.35 cents 	 (19 cents of this is covered by Provincial grants)Sewerage							.22 centsSolid waste/recycling						.18 centsWater								.15 centsParks								.04 centsAir quality							.02 centsStrategic planning						.01 centsLabour relations						.01 centsGeneral administration						.01 cents9-1-1 emergency phone						.01 cents						Total	      $1.00</PRE><H4>Where It Comes From</H4><PRE>Member municipalities 						.77 cents(tax requisitions and user charges)Provincial Government						.19 cents(mostly hospital funding)Fees and licences						.02 centsSteam sales 							.01 cents(steam generated at Burnaby Incinerator)Surplus/Revenue							.01 cents						Total	      $1.00</PRE><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#wat">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="wat">GVRD Water System</A> </H3> <P><UL> <LI>One of the largest systems in North America, covering nearly 2,000 square kilometres and serving 1.8 million people. All metro area municipalities except White Rock, Belcarra, Anmore, and Lions Bay are part of the regional system.<LI>1.1 billion litres of water a day, on average, are delivered to municipalities, most of which pay less than 12 cents per 1,000 litres.<LI>6 dams<LI>6 mountain storage lakes<LI>22 service reservoirs, located in Vancouver, North Vancouver District, North Vancouver City, Burnaby, Delta, Surrey, Coquitlam, New Westminster, and Maple Ridge.<LI>550 km of supply mains<LI>585 sq km protected watershed<LI>100,000 water quality tests (1994)<LI>Value of current assets, about $700 million<LI>Currently underway: upgrading water quality, storage capacity and other aspects of the system, at a cost of up to $1 billion.</UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#sew">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="sew">Sewerage and Drainage</A> </H3> <UL><LI>One of the largest systems in North America, covering 1,000 square kilometres with 18 municipalities and 1.8 million people.<LI>Over 1 billion litres of wastewater handled daily.<LI>5 treatment plants.<LI>450 km of trunklines and interceptors.<LI>46,000 tests (1994) evaluating plant performance.<LI>Value of current asserts, over $1 billion.<LI>Currently underway: upgrading facilities, including secondary treatment, at a cost exceeding $1 billion.</UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#air">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="air">Air Quality</A> </H3> <UL><LI>Monitoring network of 40 stations, located in Vancouver, North Vancouver, West Vancouver, Anmore, Port Moody, Coquitlam, Port Coquitlam, Langley Township, Surrey, White Rock, Delta, Richmond, New Westminster, and Burnaby. Stations in Pitt Meadows, Abbotsford, and Chilliwack are operated by the GVRD, under contract to the B.C. Environment ministry.<LI>19 stations continuously transmit data to a centralized computer.<LI>24-hour Air Quality Index (436-6767 or 1-800-665-1118) gives current air quality levels around the region.  <LI>24-hour air quality complaint line (436-6777). </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#par">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="par">GVRD Parks</A> </H3> <UL> <LI>18 regional parks, located in West Vancouver, Bowen Island, North Vancouver, UBC Endowment Lands,  Richmond, Delta, Burnaby, Surrey, Langley Township, Abbotsford, Maple Ridge, Coquitlam, and Port Moody/Belcarra.<LI>9,500 hectares (equivalent to 24 Stanley parks) in total.<LI>4.9 million visitors in 1994.<LI>Currently underway: the creation of six new regional parks and six additions to existing regional parks, under the Lower Mainland Nature Legacy Program. </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#911">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="911">9-1-1 Service</A> </H3> <UL><LI>The GVRD manages the 9-1-1 fire, police and ambulance emergency phone system throughout Greater Vancouver.<LI>The system will handle 1 million calls this year.<LI>Capable of handling calls in 150 different languages. </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#hos">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="hos">Hospital Planning and Development</A> </H3><UL><LI>The GVRD funds 40% of all hospital and extended care construction for health care facilities in the region  as well as some equipment costs. <LI>Since 1967 the GVRD has contributed nearly $350 million for health care improvements with major funding to Vancouver Hospital, Children's, B.C. Women's , St. Paul's, Richmond, Delta, Peace Arch, Surrey Memorial, Langley Memorial, Royal Columbian, Eagle Ridge, Lions Gate and other hospitals.<LI>Currently underway: projects at 20 different hospitals in Greater Vancouver, at an estimated cost of $111 million (GVRD share, $45 million). </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#hou">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="hou">GVRD Housing</A> </H3><UL><LI>Operated on a self-supporting, not-for-profit basis by the GVRD's Greater Vancouver Housing Corporation. <LI>10,000 tenants.<LI>47 projects, located in Vancouver, Burnaby, New Westminster, Richmond, Delta, Surrey, Port Coquitlam, Port Moody, Coquitlam, and North Vancouver.<LI>3,204 units, all rental. Some designed for seniors and the disabled.<LI>30% of tenants pay rent in accordance with their income.<LI>Value of current assets, about $250 million. </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#sol">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="sol">Solid Waste and Recycling</A> </H3><UL><LI>The GVRD is responsible for solid waste management and recycling promotion and co-ordination in Greater  Vancouver.<LI>The regional waste disposal system consists of an incinerator, landfill, and four transfer stations owned and operated by the GVRD, a landfill and transfer station owned by Vancouver, a landfill owned by Surrey and a privately-owned waste recovery plant under contract to the GVRD.  <LI>2.6 million tonnes of solid waste generated in the region (1994). (24% residential; 37 % industrial/commercial/institutional; 39% land clearing and building debris).<LI>30% of this waste is recycled.<LI>The GVRD this year is expected to assume regulatory responsibility for privately operated solid waste and recycling facilities. </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#str">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="str">Strategic Planning</A> </H3><UL><LI>Initiated and guided "Creating Our Future", the foundation for GVRDprograms and policies, adopted by the  Board of Directors in 1990 and updated by the Board in 1993.<LI>Works in co-operation with municipalities in developing strategies to enhance the region's livability. Does research on development trends, the economy, land use and transportation issues, and the environment.<LI>All member municipalities participate in the GVRD Strategic Planning service.<LI>Currently considering new provincial and regional legislation concerning growth management measures for the metropolitan area. </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#com">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="com">Communications and Education</A> </H3><UL> <LI>Through teacher workshops and school assemblies held in the last two years, nearly 100,000 students  received information on recycling, water conservation, wastewater management and air quality.<LI>Handles 3,000 inquiries a month from the public.<LI>Manages GVRD public consultation programs. </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#lab">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="lab">Labour Relations</A> </H3><UL> <LI> Labour Relations negotiates agreements with unions representing about 14,000 inside and outside workers  in all GVRD member municipalities except Surrey, Port Coquitlam, Anmore, Belcarra, and Lions Bay. </UL><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#emp">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="emp">GVRD Employees, By Department</A> </H3><PRE>Sewerage & Drainage		294Water				227Finance/Administration		125Parks				 70Air Quality			 63Housing				 45Strategic Planning		 27Solid Waste			 26Labour Relations		 20Communications and Education	 15Hospital Planning		 10Other				 20			Total	942 </PRE><HR>[<A HREF="#top">Top of the page</A>][<A HREF="#mor">Next</A>]<PRE></PRE>  <H3><A NAME="mor">More Information?</A> </H3><P> If you would like more information about GVRD services or funding or would like a copy of the 1994 GVRD Annual  Report please contact the Communications and Education Department, 4330 Kingsway, Burnaby,  V5H 4G8  /  Fax (604) 432-6399  / Phone (604) 432-6339<HR><P><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../go/medarch/home/smhome.gif" HSPACE=15 BORDER=0></A><A HREF="work.html"><IMG SRC="../medarch/work/worksm.gif" HSPACE=2 BORDER=0></A><BR>[<A HREF="../../index.html">GVRD Home</A>][<A HREF="work.html">Working with You</A>][<A HREF="../../finance/bro/findept.html">Finance department</A>]<BR><ADDRESS>For further information or feedback, please email us at <A HREF="mailto:webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca">webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca</A></ADDRESS></BODY></HTML>
