<!doctype html public \"-//W30//DTD W3 HTML 2.0//EN\"><!-- HTML Author:		Peter FralinCreated:	Thursday, August 10, 1995Revised: 	Thursday, August 10, 1995--><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Vancouver Compost Demonstration Garden</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000><CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A></CENTER><H1>Waste Reduction at Home</H1><H2>Composting</H2><H3>The Vancouver Compost Demonstration Garden</H3><P>In the Spring of 1990, <AHREF="">City Farmer</A>, in co-operation with the <AHREF="">City of Vancouver</A> Engineering Department, set up British Columbia's first Compost Demonstration Garden at 2150 Maple Street in Kitsilano.  The site includes a 25 squaremetre organic garden, a wide variety of rodent-resistant compost units, a Compost Hotline for telephone inquires, an indoor meeting room, a model balcony garden and a solar greenhouse. This site has become a centre for both research and information on home composting in the Province.<IMG SRC="../av_media/cityfarm.gif" ALIGN=LEFT><P>Because of the concerns of Regional Environmental Health Officers, all the bins in the garden are rodent-resistant, a design specification which hadn't been considered before. Staff members hired on a Federal Employment and Immigration Job Development Program reviewed manufactured bins from around the world, including models from Germany, Holland, England, the United States and across Canada.  At least 10 local companies  developed bins as well and these became available commercially by the summer of 1990.<P>Staff not only helped design some of the bins, but were also responsible for testing them continuously.  Large volumes of yard and food waste were processed and the merits and faults of each unit were noted.  The public was taught what wastes to mix and which method of composting worked best based on the discoveries made by the garden staff.<P>The finished compost was used in the large vegetable, fruit, herb and flower beds by both the employees and eager volunteers who were responsible for garden maintenance. Hundreds of visitors touring the demonstration site asked as many questions about gardening as they did about composting, and were inspired to make their own compost by the beauty and taste of the plants they saw.<P>Callers from across the country asked Hotline operators a variety of general questions, such as which bin to buy, how to make compost, and what went wrong with their compost pile.  Some callers had more specific questions, such as whether or not to add walnut leaves or barbecue coals, or whether a compost "starter" was helpful.  Our cordless phone allowed staff to work in the garden and still answer calls.<P>Good composting practices were promoted to thousands more people via television, radio, newspapers, magazines, and educational videos.  CBC TV's "Down To Earth" shot four separate programs from the garden which were broadcast nationally.  Staff developed a slide show presentation which they used when speaking to groups who couldn't get to the garden.  Brochures, newsletters and information sheets were also sent out on request as part of our outreach program.<P>Classes of school children came with containers and shredded newspapers to learn the secrets of worm composting.  After a one hour class and some donated red wiggler worms, they were ready to return to their schools and begin composting some of their lunch scraps.<P>The Demonstration Garden staff was able to help government agencies, community organizations and manufacturers develop educational programs and products to further benefit the public.  In recognition of this work they were awarded the 'Recycler of the Year Award' by the Greater Vancouver Regional District for 1990.<HR>[<A HREF="../../index.html>GVRD Home</A>][<A HREF="../../go/work/work.html">Working with You</A>][<A HREF="../../go/work/solid.html#menu">Solid Waste</A>][<A HREF="../../waste/bro/swcomp1.html#menu">Composting</A>][<A HREF="../../waste/bro/swcomp2.html">Gardens List</A>]<BR><ADDRESS>For further information or feedback, please email us at <A HREF="mailto:webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca">webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca</A></ADDRESS></BODY></HTML>
