</DOCHDR>
<!doctype html public \"-//W30//DTD W3 HTML 2.0//EN\"><!-- HTML Author:		Peter FralinCreated:	Thursday, August 12, 1995Revised: 	Thursday, August 12, 1995--><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>GVRD Compost Demonstration Garden</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000><CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A></CENTER><H1>Waste Reduction at Home</H1><H2>Composting</H2><H3>GVRD Compost Demonstration Garden</H3><P>In the fall of 1990, the Greater Vancouver Regional District began an innovative backyard composting program.  The GVRD in co-operation with the British Columbia Ministry of Environment, Lands and Parks and the City of Burnaby created the first government actively staffed Compost Demonstration Garden.<P> <IMG SRC="../av_media/gvrdgar1.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>Designed as a typical residential backyard, the garden's purpose is to promote the advantages and possibilities of home composting and educate residents on how to compost in their own backyard or compost with worms in apartments.  The garden is open seven (7) days a week from March until the end of October.<P>Emphasizing the need to reduce the 30 per cent organic portion of the waste stream, the Demonstration Garden offers workshops to schools and the general public and conducts group tours. Visitor response has been overwhelming as evidenced by the 8000 residents who visited the garden during the 1991 season. Residents visit the garden to find out the how, why, when and where of composting; to inquire on specific problems experienced with the process; and to view the results of using compost.<P>Assistance is provided to the public to help make the most effective choice of available rodent-resistant containers.  The results from compost bin trials provide valuable public information.  Practical trials of the compost bins include:  the weighing of carbon-rich and nitrogen-rich materials; temperature monitoring; aeration; the percentage reduction; the analysis of the quantity and quality of the compost produced. Information is also provided to the municipal recycling co-ordinators.<P>Benefits of composting are promoted through workshops that teach the basic techniques of composting. Over 38 workshops have been held. Taxpayers are made aware of money saved by reducing their waste at source, the value of compost produced and the additional savings in not purchasing fertilizers or amendments.<P> <IMG SRC="../av_media/gvrdgar2.gif" ALIGN=RIGHT>Workshops for children bring the message of how to compost in apartments, classrooms or a backyard by practical activities where children learn from hands-on participation. Over 1300 children have visited the garden and many return with their parents to see how their plants growing in compost are progressing.<P>By providing displays and workshops at community outreach events we are able to contact thousands of individuals who have never considered composting as a means of waste reduction.<P>Evaluation of the education program is by direct written feedback from teachers and residents. The increasing demand for information and popular response to subsidized bin distribution programs gives indication of the willingness of residents to play a vital role in waste reduction. About 45,000 compost bins have been distributed in the Region.<P>Compost education is only one of the initiatives undertaken by the GVRD to promote regional waste reduction goals. The GVRD Compost Demonstration Garden is one of eight in the Region. Our common goal is composting which provides an economical means of reducing the waste stream by returning organic material to the soil and being part of the natural cycle of life.<HR>[<A HREF="../../index.html>GVRD Home</A>][<A HREF="../../go/work/work.html">Working with You</A>][<A HREF="../../go/work/solid.html#menu">Solid Waste</A>][<A HREF="../../waste/bro/swcomp1.html#menu">Composting</A>][<A HREF="../../waste/bro/swcomp2.html">Gardens List</A>]<BR><ADDRESS>For further information or feedback, please email us at <A HREF="mailto:webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca">webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca</A></ADDRESS></BODY></HTML>
