<!doctype html public \"-//W30//DTD W3 HTML 2.0//EN\"><!-- HTML Author:		Peter FralinCreated:	Thursday, August 10, 1995Revised: 	Thursday, August 10, 1995--><HTML><HEAD><TITLE>Richmond Compost Demonstration Garden</TITLE></HEAD><body bgcolor=#FFFFFF text=#000000><CENTER><A HREF="../../index.html"><IMG SRC="../../go/medarch/home/head6.gif" BORDER=0></A></CENTER><H1>Waste Reduction at Home</H1><H2>Composting</H2><H3>City of Richmond Compost Demonstration Garden</H3><P>Richmond, along with many communities, is striving to reach the Provincial mandate of 50 per cent reduction in residential waste sent for disposal by the year 2000.  Many initiatives for waste reduction, reuse and recycling will be needed in order to reach this goal.<P>One of Richmond's latest initiatives, which was officially opened on Sunday, May 16, 1993, is the establishment of a Recycling Depot and Compost Demonstration Garden. This is a facility which combines the concepts of waste reduction through recycling and backyard composting in one location.<P>The goal for this facility is to reduce the residential waste stream by three per cent.<P>The purpose of the Recycling Depot and Compost Garden is to provide recycling opportunities and an educational demonstration facility for backyard composting.<P> <IMG SRC="../av_media/richmond.gif" ALIGN=LEFT>The Compost Garden is a demonstration of how backyard composting can benefit the soil and enhance lawns and gardens.  Different types of compost bins are displayed to help residents select a compost bin appropriate for their yard.  Workshops for both adults and children are offered at the garden.<P>Adults can learn about backyard composting from an expert on the subject, and children will be able to learn how composting with worms can effectively reduce garbage.<P>The Compost Demonstration Garden will also serve to support the backyard compost bin distribution programs which the City has undertaken.  Residents who want to learn more about composting can visit the Compost Garden to get tips on composting. The Depot accepts yard waste - leaves, grass clippings, brush and branches up to 10 centimetres in diameter, plants, flowers and sod.<HR>[<A HREF="../../index.html>GVRD Home</A>][<A HREF="../../go/work/work.html">Working with You</A>][<A HREF="../../go/work/solid.html#menu">Solid Waste</A>][<A HREF="../../waste/bro/swcomp1.html#menu">Composting</A>][<A HREF="../../waste/bro/swcomp2.html">Gardens List</A>]<BR><ADDRESS>For further information or feedback, please email us at <A HREF="mailto:webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca">webmaster@gvrd.bc.ca</A></ADDRESS></BODY></HTML>
