<title>SEASONAL TO INTERANNUAL PREDICTION RESEARCH</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>Diagnostic Studies of Seasonal Climate Anomalies</h1>
<hr>
<h2>Accomplishments FY95</h2>

Over the past year, CDC scientists have conducted extensive research on
mid-latitude atmosphere-ocean interactions, and interactions between the
ocean surface and deeper ocean layers.  Data analyses and upper ocean model
simulations indicate that, over parts of the extratropical oceans,
temperature anomalies form at the sea surface, penetrate into the ocean,
and then return to the surface. This 
<a href=/cdc/overview/9596/reemerge.mech.caption.html><em>recurrence mechanism</em></a> 
occurs when
thermal anomalies created by surface fluxes in one winter can remain
undisturbed in the summer seasonal thermocline and then be re-entrained
into the surface layer in the following winter. Thermal anomalies created
at the surface can also move into the permanent thermocline.  Upper ocean
data from the central north Pacific indicates that abnormally cold water
first created at the surface in the mid 1970's moved downward in pulses,
reaching depths of 400m ~2 years later. At longer time scales, some of the
cold water flowed southward following the mean circulation in the
subtropical gyre.  Thus, subsurface data may be an excellent way to detect
low frequency climate signals and to validate hypotheses of the upper ocean
circulation.
<p>
<a href=/cdc/overview/9596/reemerge.mech.caption.html>
<img src=/cdc/overview/9596/reemerge.tiny.gif 
alt="" align=middle></a> 
<a href=/cdc/overview/9596/reemerge.mech.caption.html>Illustration of the 
recurrence (re-emergence) mechanism</a>
<p>
A variety of model simulations were performed in order to study the
processes which influence midlatitude SSTs. A very long simulation in which
a mixed layer ocean model was driven by stochastic atmospheric forcing
indicated that, in addition to surface fluxes, entrainment plays an
important role in the ocean heat budget during summmer and fall.
Entrainment directly influences SSTs via the heat flux through the base of
the mixed layer, and indirectly affects SSTs by controlling the depth over
which the fluxes at the top and base of the mixed layer are distributed. A
grid of mixed layer models in the North Atlantic was able to simulate SST
variability on interannual (less than ~15 years) time scales reasonably
well when forced with observed surface flux anomalies and when coupled to
an atmospheric GCM.  Compared to a control run with specified
climatological SSTs, the coupled run also had more power at low
frequencies, due to a reduction in thermal damping and by effects related
to the recurrence mechanism.
<p>
As part of the GFDL-University consortium project, CDC and CIRES
scientists have been documenting the basic climate and climate variability
of the latest version of the GFDL GCM.  The model simulated well the North
Pacific jet, and was able to reproduce the observed mid-winter minimum in
storm activity over the North Pacific.  A detailed examination of the
model's surface flux fields has been initiated that will include
comparisons of the GFDL fluxes with corresponding fields obtained from the
NCEP Reanalysis data set.
<p>
The development of a dynamically consistent diabatic heating dataset for
1985-94 has been completed. A separate dataset of dynamically consistent
200 mb divergence fields for 1980-93 has also been generated. These
datasets were obtained by making minimal adjustments to the operational NCEP
and ECMWF wind analyses so that they satisfied the vorticity and mass
budgets. The heating fields were derived as a balance requirement in the
heat budget.


<h2>Plans FY96</h2>
<ul>
<li>Process subsurface ocean temperature records and then perform diagnostic
studies on interannual and decadal climate signals. Subsurface storage of
thermal anomalies in the seasonal thermocline can lead to the recurrence of
wintertime SST anomalies, while thermal changes in the upper main
thermocline provide a means of tracking low frequency climate variability.
<p>
<li>Perform atmosphere-ocean model experiments to assess the importance of
midlatitude air-sea interaction in the North Atlantic on climate
variability. Sea surface temperature patterns may influence both the local
atmospheric circulation and conditions downstream over Europe and thus be
important for climate prediction.
<p>
<li>Document the mean climate and climate variability in the current
version of the GFDL GCM. Both a printed and World Wide Web -accessible
version of an atlas of climate statistics from a 17-year model simulation
are being developed and will be made available to the public.
<p>
<li>Examine the atmosphere-ocean fluxes of heat, momentum, and fresh water
obtained from from the 17-year GFDL GCM run and compare the results to
estimates from the NCEP Reanalyses.
<p>
<li>Construct a dynamically consistent heating and divergent wind data set
following procedures described above with the NCEP reanalyses. These
dynamically consistent datasets will be used in the diagnosis of the
seasonal forecast skill of the NCEP model and in fundamental low-frequency
variability research.
</ul>
<hr>
