<head>
<TITLE>Overview of The NOAA Climate Diagnostics Center </TITLE>
</head>
<body>
<H1>NOAA Climate Diagnostics Center: 
<em>Advancing Understanding And Predictions of Climate Variability</em>
</h1>
<HR>
<h3>Boulder, Colorado</h3>
<h3>Randall Dole, Director</h3>
<HR>
The Climate Diagnostics Center (<b>CDC</b>), previously the 
Climate Research Division of the ERL Climate
Monitoring and Diagnostics Laboratory (<b>CMDL</b>), was
formed in 1993 to identify the nature and causes for climate 
variations on time scales ranging from months to centuries.  
The ultimate goal of this work is to develop the ability to 
predict important climate variations on these time scales.  
Short-term climate variations of interest include major 
droughts and floods over the continental U.S., and the 
global anomalies associated with El Ni&ntilde;o-Southern Oscillation 
(ENSO).  These events attract extreme public interest, 
and often have enormous social and economic consequences.  
On longer time scales, basic research goals include 
identifying the causes for decadal to centennial 
climate variations, and separating natural variability 
from anthropogenically induced climate changes in 
order to provide an improved scientific basis for public 
planning and policy decisions.  CDC has made considerable 
progress toward these goals through a coordinated program 
of diagnostic and modeling studies aimed at significantly 
advancing understanding and predictions of climate variability.

<p>
<h2>
PROJECT GOALS AND METHODOLOGY:
</h2>
Specific goals of major subprojects within the Center 
include: 
<ol>
<li>identifying key processes contributing to extreme short-term climate events, including major droughts and floods; 
<li>advancing understanding and predictions of ENSO; 
<li>developing new diagnostic techniques to better determine fundamental atmospheric quantities, such as diabatic heating; 
<li>improving monitoring and descriptions of climate variability with both surface and satellite data; 
<li>diagnosing general circulation and operational prediction model data to identify primary areas where model improvements are needed; 
<li>identifying major patterns of climate variability on decadal and longer time scales; and 
<li>investigating the role of air-sea interactions in modulating longer-term variability.
</ol>
Scientists at CDC employ a broad array of methods to achieve 
these goals, including observational diagnostic analyses, 
simple modeling studies, and analyses of forecast experiments 
obtained from sophisticated models of the atmosphere and 
oceans.  CDC studies increasingly involve comparisons of 
observational and model data, an activity essential for 
improving current research and prediction models.
<p>

<a name="data"><h2>DATA MANAGEMENT
AND DATA SET DEVELOPMENT</h2></a>

CDC
is at the forefront of data management activities in NOAA,
using new technologies and techniques to store, access,
process and display data.  
Although much of our data is used in-house,
our future plans include increased data
distribution to all interested researchers.
Most of these data are from
observational systems, but some are generated by numerical
models of the atmosphere and ocean.  Comparison of model
data with observations is important in validating existing
models and helping to develop more reliable models for
future research.<p>

Major climate data set development projects at CDC include 
the 
<a href=/coads/>Comprehensive Ocean-Atmosphere Data Set</a> 
(<b>COADS</b>)
and the 
<a href=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/gcps/gcps.html>Global Climate 
Perspectives System</a> (<b>GCPS</b>), 
which are both collaborative projects with the 
<a href="http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/ncdc.html">
National Climatic Data Center</a> (<b>NCDC</b>).
These high-quality data sets significantly 
improve NOAA's capabilities for monitoring climatic trends, 
e.g., in surface temperatures and precipitation. 
The COADS project is a
cooperative effort between CDC and the 
<a href="http://cires.colorado.edu">
Cooperative Institute for Research in
Environmental Sciences</a> (<b>CIRES</b>), the 
<a href ="http://www.ucar.edu/metapage.html">
National Center for Atmospheric Research</a> (<b>NCAR</b>), 
and NCDC.
COADS Release 1a data
now provide a 1980-93 extension beyond the 
original COADS Release 1 1854-1979
period, and COADS Release 1b observational data, 
to be completed in 1996, will
provide an update for the approximate period 1946-79.

<p> 
CDC also manages large observational and model 
data sets that are frequently used in climate research 
studies within and outside CDC, including the National
Centers for Environmental Predication (NCEP)/NCAR 
reanalysis data set which, 
upon completion, will have a volume of approximately 1.2 
terabytes.  
(COADS Release 1a and 1b data are also key 
components of the Reanalysis data input).
CDC's data management group is also a leader 
in developing new techniques to simplify access to and 
display of climate data for the larger scientific community.  
The CDC data holdings may be browsed via the World Wide Web 
interface to the 
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/CDCData.pl">CDC data archives</a>.  
For further information 
on how to access CDC's research data sets, contact 
<em>cdcdata@cdc.noaa.gov</em>.<p>

CDC is currently participating in
the formation of a cooperative data distribution
system. This system is intended to be a first step in
cooperative data management between CDC and other 
groups which are active in data management and/or use the data
in question.  This system 
will strive to provide unique data
sets, for example, COADS, NMC reanalysis, ocean analysis,
possibly TOGA-TAO, and model data. <p>

<h2>RESULTS AND ACCOMPLISHMENTS:</h2>
Some significant results and accomplishments of the 
subprojects are listed below.
<ul>
<li>An observational study examined the processes 
contributing to the evolution of the extreme heat
 wave/droughts in the midwestern U.S. in 1980 and 
1988.  The results showed that these extreme events 
evolved in two stages, with the first or development 
stage being forced from sources over the Pacific, 
and the second stage due mainly to anomalous boundary 
conditions (primarily reductions in soil moisture) 
in the drought regions.  This suggests that, once 
established, major heat wave/droughts tend to be 
self-perpetuating.  Another implication of this 
study is that, in order to properly simulate or 
predict long-term droughts, it will be necessary 
for models to properly incorporate the effects of 
land surface processes.<p>

<font size=2>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig3.html">
<img align=BOTTOM src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig3_small.gif">
Figure 3. This is a link to the larger version of this image.</a><br>
     Drought of 1988:  Illustration of the surface heat balance over the
northern Plains during the evolution of the major 1988 summer heat wave --
drought.  Through June, surface evaporation rates (shown by LH) were near
normal, indicating that other processes were responsible for the
initiation of the heat wave -- drought.  By July, however, evaporation
rates had dropped to levels much below normal, and were compensated
largely by increases in sensible heating (SH).<p>
</font>

<li>Several investigations considered various 
aspects of ENSO.  One study identified the 
climatic impacts of ENSO through observational 
analyses of El Ni&ntilde;o or "warm events" 
and 23 La Ni&ntilde;a or "cold events."  The results 
showed that, during the December through February 
period following the development of a warm event, 
a large fraction of the global tropics experiences 
above normal temperatures.  Above normal temperatures 
also dominate Alaska, the northern midwestern states, 
and most of Canada, while anomalously cold conditions 
occur in the southeastern United States. Nearly equal 
and opposite signals are seen for cold events.  During 
winter, warm event precipitation is enhanced over the 
southeastern U.S. and southern South America, while 
much of Australia, southern Africa and the Amazon suffer 
precipitation deficits.  Identification of such 
relationships aids long-range weather forecasts, 
since El Ni&ntilde;o is relatively predictable up 
to a year in advance.<p>

<font size=2>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig4.html">
<img align=BOTTOM src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig4_small.gif">
Figure 4. This is a link to the larger version of this image.</a><br>
     Average temperature anomaly during December through February
following the development of El Ni&ntilde;o.  The anomalies are based on
25 El Ni&ntilde;o events from 1877 through 1986.  Anomalies are given in
degrees C according to the color scale at the bottom of the plot, and are
based on a 1951-1980 climatology.<p>

<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig5.html">
<img align=BOTTOM src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig5_small.gif">
Figure 5. This is a link to the larger version of this image.</a><br>
     Average precipitation anomaly during December through February
following the development of El Ni&ntilde;o.  The anomalies are based on
25 El Ni&ntilde;o events from 1877 through 1986.  Anomalies are given in
millimeters of precipitation during the three months according to the
color scale at the bottom of the plot, and are based on a 1951-1980
climatology.<p>
</font>

<li>A major research focus at CDC is on improving predictive 
skill on seasonal and longer time scales. One study 
evaluated the seasonal predictive skill of two nearly 
identical versions of the National Meteorological Center's 
climate model.  Skill was evaluated by the model's ability 
to produce, on average, seasonal circulation patterns over
 North America.  Although the two models had identical sea 
surface temperatures, one was significantly better for 
predicting seasonal temperature anomalies.  These results 
indicate that biases in current climate models can significantly 
degrade forecast quality and reliability, and suggest 
that further gains in seasonal forecast skill are likely 
through continued development of climate models.<p>

<font size=2>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig6.html">
<img align=BOTTOM src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig6_small.gif">
Figure 6. This is a link to the larger version of this image.</a><br>
     The top panel shows the composite North American land temperature
anomaly during the winter season for the 7 strong El Ni&ntilde;o events
since 1950.  On average, most of North America is anomalously warm during
El Ni&ntilde;o.  The largest departures occur across Canada and the
northern tier of the United States.  A small region over the southeast
United States tends to be slightly colder than normal during El
Ni&ntilde;o winters.  The lower panel shows the composite North American
land temperatureanomaly during the winter season as simulated by a climate
model.  The climate model has been forced with the ocean surface
temperatures observed during El Ni&ntilde;o.  Note that the climate model
is capable of reproducing the essential features of the observed weather
anomalies, and suggests that such models can provide useful forecast
information.<p>
</font>

<li>In another study, a simple empirical dynamical model 
of ENSO was developed whose predictive skill at lead times 
of up to a year is comparable to that of comprehensive 
global coupled ocean-atmosphere models.  In addition to 
providing tropical sea surface temperature (SST) forecasts, 
this simple model is being used to elucidate the basic 
mechanisms of tropical SST evolution and to diagnose errors 
in the more complicated coupled models.<p>

<font size=2>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig7.html">
<img align=BOTTOM src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig7_small.gif">
Figure 7. This is a link to the larger version of this image.</a><br>
     Forecasts of seasonal anomalies in Pacific sea-surface temperatures
through Spring 1996.  Forecasts are based upon Spring 1995 initial
conditions, and are derived from a simple model developed at CDC.  Contour
interval is 0.2 degrees Centigrade.<p>
</font>

<li>The ultimate cause of atmospheric motions is spatial 
variations in heating and, therefore, determining the 
location and intensity of atmospheric heat sources is a 
fundamental problem in meteorology.  Scientists at CDC 
have developed a new method for estimating atmospheric 
heat sources that provides very encouraging results, 
and are now preparing a global heating dataset for widespread 
dissemination.  This dataset should prove extremely useful 
for verifying climate models and satellite-derived estimates 
of precipitation, and consequently improving our ability 
to monitor climate variability and detect climate changes.<p>

<li>In studies with <a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~climsat/">satellite 
data</a>, CDC scientists have actively participated in the 
Global Energy and Water Cycle Experiment (<b>GEWEX</b>).  
As part of this work, they have developed a new technique 
to improve estimates of the variability of atmospheric water 
vapor in space and time.  Their analyses show that during the 
1982-83 major ENSO event air in the tropical upper troposphere 
became warmer, as expected, but also drier, implying a 
negative feedback effect from water vapor in the global 
warming sense.  This contradicts the IPCC consensus view 
that the upper tropospheric water vapor feedback is always 
large and positive, and emphasizes the importance of such 
analyses in studies of climate and global change.<p>

<font size=2>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig8.html">
<img align=BOTTOM src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig8_small.gif">
Figure 8. This is a link to the larger version of this image.</a><br>
     Thirteen years of HIRS channel 12 data from the NOAA polar orbiter
satellites is shown for the winter (DJF) and summer (JJA) seasons.  HIRS
channel 12 data are used to observe upper tropospheric water vapor (UTWV). 
Low temperatures indicate a relatively wet upper troposphere and high
temperatures indicate a dry upper troposphere.  A well-defined seasonal
shift in UTWV occurs in subtropical regions (10N-30N and 10S-30S) with the
most significant changes occurring in monsoon regions such as Central
America and India.  These data will play a significant role in
understanding the global hydrologic cycle and assessing climate issues
such as greenhouse warming since no other dataset provides a greater
observational sample of UTWV.<p>
</font>

<li>Several studies at CDC have considered various aspects 
of longer term climate variability.  Of particular interest 
is the role of air-sea interactions in climate and climate 
change.  Decadal and longer term variations have been documented 
in winds and sea surface temperature (SST) variability over the 
North Atlantic, and thermal variations in the upper 500 m of the
 North Pacific have been described since 1970.  The latter study 
identified relationships between the cooling trend observed in 
mid-Pacific SST's from the 1970's to late 1980's and temperature 
anomalies in the deeper ocean.  Another study showed how sea 
surface temperature anomalies that formed near the surface in 
winter could remain intact below surface during summer, and then 
reappear at the surface the following winter, thereby potentially 
influencing interannual climate variability.<p>

<font size=2>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig9.html">
<img align=BOTTOM src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc/overview/fig9_small.gif">
Figure  9. This is a link to the larger version of this image.</a><br>
     Time-depth plot of the seasonal temperature anomalies (degrees C) to
a depth of 400 meters in the central North Pacific, illustrating the large
interannual to decadal variability in this region.<p>
</font>

</ul>

<h2>FUTURE WORK:</h2>
Future work at CDC will extend the research activities 
described above, in direct support of three primary NOAA 
Strategic Plan goals:  Advancing Short-Term Forecast and 
Warning Services, Implementing Seasonal to Interannual Forecasts, 
and Predicting Decadal to Centennial Climate Changes.<p>

Studies of extreme events will examine the relationships between 
extreme events and ENSO, the roles of different physical 
processes in producing severe droughts and floods, and the 
potential predictability of extreme events.  Process studies 
will continue on ENSO and air-sea interactions, along with 
collaborative studies with the NMC Coupled Model project to 
improve seasonal to interannual climate predictions.  Long-term 
variability studies will examine further the processes contributing 
to decadal variability of the atmosphere-ocean system, as well 
as decadal to century variability in precipitation and other 
climate measures.  An important objective in future work at CDC 
will be to identify and clarify the linkages between climate 
variability on different time scales; for example, how ENSO 
influences the occurrence and duration of an extreme event such 
as a major drought or flood, and the relationships between 
ENSO and decadal-to-centennial variability.<p>

