<HTML>
<HEAD>
<title>Linear Inverse Modelling ENSO Forecast: 12/96 El Nino SST</title>
<!-- Changed by: Cathy Smith,  2-Dec-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov">
<IMG alt="Climate Daignostics Center" SRC="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc_images/banner.gif"></a>
</center>
<h1>Linear Inverse Modelling ENSO Forecast (12/96)</h1>
<a href="/~cas/ElNino.forecast.html">Obtain forecast history data</a><br>
<a href="#maps">Skip to forecast maps</a><br>

 <P>
Predictions of Nino 3 SSTA (green solid line) using linear inverse modeling procedure discussed in Penland and Magorian (1993: J. Climate, 6, 1067-1076), along with verification field (solid red line).  Dashed lines indicate one standard deviation error bars appropriate to a stable linear system driven by stochastic forcing. SST anomaly data have been provided by NCEP, courtesy of R. W. Reynolds.  Anomalies were calculated relative to the standard 1950-1979 COADS climatology and projected onto 20 leading EOFs both for the training and verification periods.

 <P>
<IMG alt="JJA.plots" SRC="current.nin3.GIF">
<hr>
<A NAME="maps">
Forecasts of SST anomalies projected onto 20 leading EOF's, based on September-October-November 1996 initial conditions. SST anomalies have been calculated relative to the standard 1950-1979 COADS climatology both for the training period (COADS data: 1950-1984) and for these forecasts.  SST data used in these forecasts have been provided by NCEP, courtesy of R. W. Reynolds. Prediction by linear inverse modeling is described in Penland and Magorian (1993: J. Climate, 6, 1067-1076).  Contour interval is 0.2 degrees C. 
 <P>
<IMG alt="JJA96 maps" SRC="current.map.gif">
<address><a href="/~mcp/">Cecile Penland</a></address>
<address><a href="/~cas/">prepared by: Cathy Smith</a></address>
<address>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/">The Climate Diagnostics Center</a></address>

</BODY>
</HTML>
