<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>slide2.html</TITLE>
<!-- Create by: Andy Loughe,  4-Oct-1996 -->
<!--$Id: slide2.html,v 1.1 1996/10/11 16:21:23 jac Exp $-->
<!--
$Log: slide2.html,v $
Revision 1.1  1996/10/11 16:21:23  jac
Initial revision

-->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff">

<CENTER>

<IMG ALT="NOAA/Climate Diagnostics Center"
SRC="/cdc_images/banner.gif">

<p>
<FONT SIZE=5 FONT COLOR="000080">
Causes and Potential Predictability of
Extreme Climate and Weather Events <BR>

<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="ee0000">
<I> Randall M. Dole </I> <BR>
<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="000000">
<B> -2- </B>
</CENTER>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="000000">

     A more difficult, but crucial, question is: what were the 
causes for the observed jet stream variations?  Present 
interpretations should be regarded as preliminary, but at 
this point there 
is substantial evidence that variations in the jet stream and 
associated drought conditions over the Southwest were due in part 
to abnormally cold sea surface temperatures over the central 
and eastern equatorial Pacific, called a La Nia (or cold) event.  
La Nia is basically the flip side of El Nio, which is 
characterized by abnormally warm waters over the same area. <P>

       Evidence supporting the La Nia - Southwest drought 
connection includes: observational studies of the relationships 
between El Nio,  La Nia and precipitation variability (an 
example is given in the next section); diagnostic studies showing 
the relationships between estimated changes in tropical 
precipitation patterns and corresponding changes in the 
midlatitude jet stream;  and experiments with the NOAA National 
Centers for Environmental Prediction (NCEP) coupled 
ocean-atmosphere prediction model indicating that sea surface 
temperature conditions as observed over the past year are likely to 
be associated with suppressed rainfall over the Southwest and 
Southern Plains.  It therefore appears likely that La Nia was an 
important contributing factor to the Southwest drought, 
although it should not be considered as the sole cause. <P>

       The situation in the East is again more complex, due in part 
to the more variable weather patterns and associated precipitation
systems, as well as the less systematic influence of La Nia 
on this region. One important influence on the East's weather 
mentioned by Dr. Ropelewski was the unusual intensity and 
persistence of a particular large-scale flow pattern called the 
"North Atlantic Oscillation", or NAO. The NAO is especially 
important in accounting for temperature variability over the 
Northern Hemisphere.  It is also closely linked to changes in 
storm tracks over the Atlantic and adjacent regions, including 
the U.S. east coast, and to snow-cover variability over North 
America and Europe.  It has the peculiar property that it usually 
displays relatively little persistence from month-to-month - 
indeed, its persistence from last fall through this spring was 
very unusual - but has a somewhat higher tendency to recur 
from one winter to the next.  Although we suspect that this 
recurrence property is related to sea-surface temperature 
variability, most likely over the North Atlantic, a definite link has 
yet to be established. <P>

<P>
<B> Potential Predictability of Extreme Events </B>
<P>

       Extreme event prediction at extended range (beyond several 
days) is an emerging area of research within NOAA, and is 
complementary to NOAA's current efforts in such areas as 
severe thunderstorm, tornado and hurricane predictions.  A 
basic goal of this research is to identify regions and time 
periods where the risk of extreme events is significantly increased 
(or decreased). <P>

       In considering problems in weather and climate prediction, 
it is vital to recognize that weather is governed by chaotic 
dynamics, so that small differences in initial states, the "flap of 
a butterfly's wings" in the words of Edward Lorenz, can eventually 
lead to large differences in the atmosphere's behavior.  As a 
consequence, the ability to predict the precise sequence of 
weather events is intrinsically limited.  Tentative estimates 
place an average upper bound for skillful weather prediction at 
a few weeks, but exceptions extending beyond this range can be 
found. <P>

      But does this mean that beyond some time period, say a 
month, all hope for useful predictions is lost?   Emphatically 
not, if instead of attempting to predict the precise sequence of 
events (today will be fair, tomorrow rainy, etc.), the goal is 
changed to attempting to predict the relative likelihood of various 
kinds of events.  At the heart of climate prediction, then, is 
the problem of determining how the probability distributions of 
various quantities, such as temperature and precipitation, will 
change given an initial atmospheric state and interactions with 
other components of the climate system, such as sea surface 
temperatures, soil moisture, ice and snow cover, vegetation, and 
- in some cases - even us (anthropogenic effects). <P>

<FONT SIZE=4>
<CENTER>

<A HREF="index.shtml">[Prev]</A> 
<B>p.</B>
<A HREF="index.shtml">1</A> 
<B>2</B> 
<A HREF="slide3.html">3</A> 
<A HREF="slide4.html">4</A> 
<A HREF="slide3.html">[Next]</A> 
</CENTER>

</BODY>
</HTML>




</DOC>
