</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff">

<CENTER>

<IMG ALT="NOAA/Climate Diagnostics Center"
SRC="/cdc_images/banner.gif">

<BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=5 FONT COLOR="000080">
Causes and Potential Predictability of
Extreme Climate and Weather Events <BR>

<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="ee0000">
<I> Randall M. Dole </I> <BR>
<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="000000">
<B> -3- </B>
</CENTER>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="000000">

     Figure 2 is a schematic diagram illustrating how a simple 
shift in a probability distribution can influence the relative 
likelihood of various outcomes.  We might imagine the shift as 
reflecting the effect of some condition, such as La Nia, on the 
precipitation over a region, say, the Southwest.  What is striking 
in this figure is that even a relatively modest shift in the mean 
can have a substantial impact on the probabilities at the tails of 
the distribution - the "extreme events".  In particular, extreme 
events on one side of the distribution become much more likely, 
while those on the other side become much less likely. <P>

<CENTER>
<IMG ALT="" SRC="dole2.gif">
</CENTER> 
<P> <CENTER> <B> Figure 2 </B> </CENTER> <P>

      As extreme events often have the greatest societal effects, 
this shift in probabilities has potentially important implications, 
and any foreknowledge of such a shift would have potentially 
useful applications.  <P>

       It must be emphasized that various physical effects enter 
into the fray, either increasing or decreasing the likelihood of 
extreme events.   Such "feedback" effects are important 
considerations in identifying possible climate trends, as described by 
Dr. Karl of NCDC, and in the possibility of experiencing 
"climate surprises", as discussed by Dr. Overpeck of NGDC.  In 
general, then, the climate prediction problem is much more 
complex than forecasting a simple shift - we really need to 
predict the shape of the whole distribution.  <P>

<FONT SIZE=4>
<CENTER>

<A href="slide2.html">[Prev]</A> 
<B>p.</B>
<A HREF="index.shtml">1</A> 
<A HREF="slide2.html">2</A> 
<B>3</B> 
<A HREF="slide4.html">4</A> 
<A HREF="slide4.html">[Next]</A> 
</CENTER>

</BODY>
</HTML>













</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>WT13-B02-209</DOCNO>
<DOCOLDNO>IA002-000022-B043-117</DOCOLDNO>
<DOCHDR>
