<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>slide4.html</TITLE>
<!-- Create by: Andy Loughe,  4-Oct-1996 -->
<!--$Id: slide4.html,v 1.1 1996/10/11 16:21:35 jac Exp $-->
<!--
$Log
-->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="ffffff">

<CENTER>

<IMG ALT="NOAA/Climate Diagnostics Center"
SRC="/cdc_images/banner.gif">

<BR><BR>
<FONT SIZE=5 FONT COLOR="000080">
Causes and Potential Predictability of
Extreme Climate and Weather Events <BR>

<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="ee0000">
<I> Randall M. Dole </I> <BR>
<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="000000">
<B> -4- </B>
</CENTER>

<P>
<FONT SIZE=3 FONT COLOR="000000">

  So, how do we do this?  There are two major approaches: 
first, through analysis of past behavior (an empirical approach) 
and, second, through application of numerical forecasting 
models employing a relatively new technique called ensemble 
predictions.  <P>

      Figure 3 illustrates how the first approach can be used to 
estimate the effects of La Nia and El Nio events on very dry 
vs. very wet winters in the Southwest.  The particular example 
is for Texas, which experienced a severe drought last winter. 
The results are derived from observational data over the period 
1895-1995, and "very dry" and "very wet" are defined, respectively, 
as the top twenty driest and wettest winters during this 
period. <P>

<CENTER>
<IMG ALT="" SRC="dole3.gif">
</CENTER> 
<P> <CENTER> <B> Figure 3 </B> </CENTER> <P>

       It is clear from this figure that La Nia and El Nio events 
significantly influence the relative likelihood of very wet vs. 
very dry winters in Texas.  In particular, during La Nia, as 
occurred last year, very dry winters are relatively much more 
likely, and very wet winters are less likely (indeed, in this 
analysis no very wet winters occurred in conjunction with La Nia 
events, although this does not rule out the possibility that such a 
concurrence may happen at some time).  Roughly the reverse 
situation holds during El Nio years, with an increased risk of 
very wet winters and reduced risk of very dry winters.  It should 
be noted that the occurrence of La Nia does not guarantee a 
very dry winter - again, other factors are involved - but it 
does shift the probability distribution in such a way as to make 
its occurrence, and therefore a possible drought, more likely.  <P>

      An alternative approach to estimating shifts in probability 
distributions is through ensemble predictions. One of the 
disadvantages of empirical techniques is that the data sample size is 
much smaller than desirable for many purposes, including the 
estimation of extreme event risks.  Computer forecast models 
that can simulate atmospheric behavior provide one possibility 
for overcoming this small sample problem (another way, which 
is to wait several hundred years for sufficient data, seems less 
appealing).   <P>

      The ensemble prediction approach is essentially a version of 
a "Monte Carlo" strategy.   Think of  nature as loading  the 
"weather dice"  each season, and  the problem  being to estimate 
how the dice are loaded, before the dice are actually rolled.  The 
basis of ensemble predictions is to run prediction models many 
times from slightly different initial conditions, and then to 
estimate the probability distributions from the outcomes of the 
different model runs.  The choice of different initial conditions 
reflects both the incomplete nature of climate observations and 
the fact that the atmosphere's evolution is very sensitive to these 
uncertainties.  <P>

      For the experimental seasonal predictions with the NCEP 
model mentioned earlier, ensemble forecasts consisting of nine 
model runs (out to two seasons in advance) are performed 
monthly.  Ultimately, predictions so derived will be blended 
with current statistical-empirical methods for seasonal forecasting.  
For shorter periods (out to two weeks), ensemble forecasts 
from seventeen separate model runs are performed daily.  <P>

      Although research is still in its early stages, preliminary 
results are encouraging and indicate that ensemble predictions 
may be useful in increasing the lead times for alerting the public 
and decision makers of possible risks of severe large-scale 
weather events.  This increased lead time should be useful in 
reducing human and economic losses due to high impact 
weather, such as the U.S. has experienced this past year.  <P>
  

<FONT SIZE=4>
<CENTER>

<A HREF="slide3.html">[Prev]</A> 
<B>p.</B>
<A HREF="index.shtml">1</A> 
<A HREF="slide2.html">2</A> 
<A HREF="slide3.html">3</A> 
<B>4</B> 

</CENTER>

</BODY>
</HTML>
