</nobr>
<hr>

<h1 align=center>PACS</h1>


<h2 align=center> A Study of Hydrological Processes in the PACS Region Using Multispectral
Satellite Observations </h2>

Investigators:  <A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~bates">John Bates</A>,
                <A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~wkb">Wesley Berg</A>, and
                <A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~qy">Qian Ye</A> <br>
Program: <a href="http://tao.atmos.washington.edu/pacs/">PanAmerican Climate Studies</a>

<P>
Understanding the role of hydrological processes, and rainfall in particular,
on short-term climate variability in the PACS regions is critical to improving
models and the subsequent climate prediction efforts.  Due to the lack of
in-situ observations over the east Pacific, however, the hydrology of this
region and the dynamics of moisture transport between the east Pacific and the
Americas is poorly understood.  The pilot field observation program planned
over the east Pacific intertropical convergence zone for September 1997 will
provide an excellent basis for studying in detail the hydrology of this region,
especially for investigating interactions within the marine boundary.  Although
the field campaign will provide valuable information for studying small-scale
processes and for validating satellite retrievals, concurrent satellite
observations are needed to understand the large-scale dynamics and the
resulting interactions with hydrological processes over the continents.
<P>
Accurately determining rainfall along the east Pacific ITCZ has been
identified as a priority for the PACS program due to its importance in
influencing seasonally-varying precipitation over the American continents.
As shown in <A HREF="images/figure1.gif">Figure 1</A>, however,
differences between rainfall processes
in this region and the west Pacific have resulted in widely varying
estimates from currently available satellite retrieval techniques.
We hypothesize that the convection within the east Pacific ITCZ is controlled
largely by two processes: 1) low-level moisture transport converging into
the ITCZ, and 2) subsidence and drying of the upper troposphere above the
ITCZ.  These processes are unique to the east Pacific ITCZ and have
given rise to the large discrepancies in estimates of precipitation and
hence latent heat release and resultant seasonal to interannual circulation
anomalies.  We propose, therefore, to study the impact of low-level moisture
transport and upper level moisture variability on precipitation within the
east Pacific ITCZ using a variety of satellite remote sensing data combined
with in-situ observations to be taken by the PACS field program.
<P>
A number of satellite data sets are currently available which will be used
to investigate our hypothesis as well as to identify features of interest
and provide a basis climatology for the field campaign.  The satellite data
sets will include rainfall, cloud liquid water, integrated water vapor, and
ice scattering information from SSM/I, cloud top temperature from OLR
measurements, and vertical water vapor information from both the SSM/T2
moisture sounder and HIRS.  In addition, we will investigate the use of
SSM/T2 data for estimating cloud liquid water and rainfall over the continents
for warm rain situations which cannot be identified from a scattering signature
using SSM/I.  Measurements from the field program will be used to validate the
satellite retrievals and to study related small-scale physical processes.
Finally, comparisons between the satellite retrieved fields and model analysis
will be performed to identify deficiencies in the models.
<p>
<A
HREF="images/figure1.gif"><IMG
alt="Figure 1"
SRC="images/figure1.tiny.gif"> Figure 1</A>

<P>
