<h1 align=center>Ocean Winds</h1>

<h2 align=center>Observation and modeling studies of surface wind speed and direction using microwave emission and backscatter from the ocean surface</h2>

Principal Investigator:  <a href="/~bates/">Dr. John J. Bates</a>
<br>

Institution:  NOAA/ERL Climate Diagnostics Center

<p>
<h3>Abstract</h3>
The ultimate goal of this research is the production of a
global ocean surface wind climatology using satellite passive and active
microwave data for use in climate monitoring and modeling.  This will be
accomplished by improving our understanding of the physics of the
radiative transfer, conducting comparisons of the remote sensing data
with in situ observations, and by analysis of the time/space scales of
variability captured by the remotely sensed data.  These results will
then be applied to the implementation of a two-dimensional variational
assimilation scheme to obtain an optimum objective analysis of ocean
wind.
<p>
<h3>Results</h3>
Wind speed and direction retrievals from the ERS-1
scatterometer show algorithms tuned using meteorological model wind
fields have significant biases versus algorithms that are tuned using
independent in situ buoy observations.  We have ported the 2-dimensional
variational assimilation method (VAM) of Dr. R. Atlas of NASA GSFC to
our system and are evaluating the impact of our ERS-1 scatterometer
algorithm on the method.  We plan to use the VAM in the future to
assimilate SSM/I radiance data for wind speed and direction.  We have
been evaluating the evidence for a wind direction signal in SSM/I data
using buoy wind matches, empirical techniques, and matches with the
ERS-1 scatterometer.  Results to date are mixed; there is a wind
direction signal which we have extracted using neural network
techniques, but we have not had success reproducing the empirical
results of Wentz.

<p>

<h3>Recent Publications</h3>

Rufenach, C. L., J. J. Bates, and S. Tosini, 1996: ERS-1 scatterometer
measurements: Part 1, the relationship between radar cross-section and
buoy wind in two oceanic regions.  Accepted by IEEE Trans. Geosci.
<p>
Bates, J. J., and K. C. McColl, 1995: Observational and theoretical
evidence for a wind direction signal in SSM/I data.  Presented at IAPSO
XXI General Assembly.
<p>
Bates, J. J., and K. C. McColl, 1996: Assessing the Ocean Surface Vector
Wind Signal in SSM/I Data Using Neural Networks.  Presented at IGARSS
96.
<p>
Rufenach, C. L., and J. J. Bates, 1996: Comparison of four ERS-1
scatterometer wind retrieval algorithms with buoy measurements.
Submitted to JGR Oceans.

