<h1 align=center>GAME: GEWEX Asian Monsoon Experiment </h1>


<h2 align=center> Climatological Study on the Hydrological Processes and
Cloud-Radiation Interaction in the GAME Region Using Multispectral
Satellite Observations </h2>

Investigators:  <A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~qy">Qian Ye</A>,
	        <A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~bates">John Bates</A>, and
                <A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~wkb">Wesley Berg</A> <br>

Program:<A HREF="/~qy/GAME/QXPMEX/qxpmex_intro.html"> QXPMEX II </a>,
	<A HREF="/~qy/GAME/HUBEX/hubex_intro.html"> HUBEX </a>,
	<A HREF="http://www.ihas.nagoya-u.ac.jp/game/index.html"> GAME </a>, 
	<A HREF="http://www.cais.net/gewex/gewex.html"> GEWEX </a>

<P>
GAME <A HREF="images/game.gif"> (map) </a>
is a subprogram under  <A HREF="http://www.cais.net/gewex/gewex.html">
the Global Energy and Water Experiment (GEWEX) </a>
as a WCRP sponsored international program to study the water
and energy balance of Asian monsoon in particulr. One of the essential
scientific requirements for GAME is to understand the physical bases of
the seasonal forecast of the Asian monsoon, and to improve the models
for predicting and assessing the regional hydro-meteorological conditions
and water resources of monsoon Asia under the anthropogenic as well as
natural climate changes.
<P>
GAME is focused on atmosphere-land interaction and proposed to
do six regional experiments over
<ul>
  <LI>    the equatorial rain forest region of southeast Asia
       
  <LI>    tropical monsoon region in south and southeast Asia

  <LI>    subtropical and midlatitude humid region of East Asia
	<A HREF="/~qy/GAME/HUBEX/hubex_intro.html">
         The Huaihe River Basin Experiment </A>

  <LI>    Tibetan Plateau <A HREF="/~qy/GAME/QXPMEX/qxpmex_intro.html"> (QXPMEX II) </a>

  <LI>    permafrost region in Siberia

  <LI>    arid region in Central Asia
</ul>
<P>
Cooperated with scientists from the LSSR, Peking University, People's Republic of
China, our study is focus on the study of intraseasonal and interannual 
variations over the GAME region, HUBEX and QXPMEX regions in particular, by using
multispectral satellite observations and NMC global grid analysis data stored in 
house. Another project we involve with Chinese scientists is
<A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~qy/SCSMEX/intro.html">
the South China Sea Monsoon Experiment (SCSMEX) </a> 
which will start in 1997 and coincide with the GAME's regional experiment.
The SCSMEX is highly complementary
to GAME in providing information on the early onset of the Asian monsoon over
the oceanic region in the SCS and therefore provides a more complete description
of the Asia monsoon coupled atmosphere-ocea-land system.
<P>
As the first step, we are working on <A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~qy/SCSMEX/scsmex_study.html"> the study of climatological features
in the South China Sea region during summer monsoon onset </a> by using NMC global
grid analysis data and OLR data. 
<p>
     
     <img alt="" src="images/go_back.gif"><a href="index.shtml">Satellite home page.</a>

