<html> <head>
<title>NOAA/CDC Satellite Reseach: TOVS Pathfinder</title>
<link rev=made href="mailto:ewc@cdc.noaa.gov"></head>

<body>
<p align=center>
<nobr><a
href="index.shtml"><img
align=top border=0
src="images/buttons/home.gif" height=47 width=408 
alt="Satellite Home"></a><a

href="/"><img
align=top border=0
src="images/buttons/cdc.gif" height=47 width=91
alt="CDC Home"></a>

<br><a
href="research.html"><img
align=top border=0
src="images/buttons/researchh.gif" height=31 width=73
alt="*Research*"></a><a

href="people.html"><img
align=top border=0
src="images/buttons/people.gif" height=31 width=57 
alt="People"></a><a

href="publications.html"><img
align=top border=0
src="images/buttons/publications.gif" height=31 width=91
alt="Publications"></a><a

href="products.html"><img
align=top border=0
src="images/buttons/products.gif" height=31 width=122
alt="Climate Products"></a><a

href="rel_links.html"><img
align=top border=0
src="images/buttons/links.gif" height=31 width=99
alt="Related Links"></a><a

href="theindex.html"><img
align=top border=0
src="images/buttons/index.gif" height=31 width=57
alt="Index"></a>
</nobr>
<hr>
<h1 align=center>TOVS Pathfinder</h1>


<a href="itsc.html">ITSC (International TOVS Study Conference) and related information and data</a>

<h2 align=center> Production and Analysis of a TOVS Radiance Data Set </h2>

Investigator:  <A HREF="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~bates">John Bates</A><br>
Program:  <a href="http://xtreme.gsfc.nasa.gov/pathfinder/">NASA</a> / <a href="http://pegasus.nesdis.noaa.gov/pathfinder.html">NOAA</a> Pathfinder<br>

<p>
Atmospheric water vapor is the most important greenhouse gas.  Water vapor
absorbs Earth emitted infrared radiation and remits this radiation at a lower
temperature.  Thus, in the climate system, water vapor acts as a moderating
influence on the planetary atmosphere.  In numerical model simulations of
anthropogenic climate change, water vapor is a significant positive feedback
mechanism enhancing the initial warming by anthropogenic gases by up to a
factor of two.  The radiative effects of upper tropospheric water vapor,
however, can compensate the radiative effects of changes in total column
water vapor and mitigate the strong water vapor feedback.  Analysis of TOVS
operational clear column water vapor brightness temperature data shown that,
in the present climate, changes in upper tropospheric water vapor can lead
to a net drying of the tropical upper troposphere, or a negative water vapor
feedback.  If this is the case, then model simulations of global warming
substantially overestimate the amount of warming likely to occur from
anthropogenic greenhouse gases.
<p>
On seasonal to interannual time scales there has been little progress in
prediction of large-scale atmospheric circulation changes that accompany
changes in surface forcing such as ENSO warm events and soil moisture
feedback.  We believe this is due to a lack of understanding of the response
of the hydrological cycle to such boundary forcing.  Analysis of a TOVS
radiance data set will help us better understand the changes in the
atmospheric hydrological cycle that result from changes in boundary forcing
on seasonal to interannual time scales.
<p>
The TOVS operational clear column radiance data set used for the studies to
date have several limitations for climate and global change studies.  First,
the operational processing algorithm has changed over time so that
discontinuities occur in the data set.  Second, the coating on the first
four HIRS/2 instruments suffered from a serious signal variation between
8-9.5 microns due to scan angle dependent polarization absorption losses.
Finally, the pre-launch calibration of the HIRS/2 water vapor channels is
uncertain because the calibration was not performed in a vacuum, but in an
open laboratory with an uncertain amount of water vapor in the path.  All
three of these problems must be carefully addresses to make the TOVS
Pathfinder data set useful for climate and global change research.
<p>
<h3>Results from prior research</h3>
Analysis of the adjusted anomaly time series shows the water vapor anomalies
in the tropics and subtropics (Figure 1).  Comparison of these data with
outgoing longwave radiation and sea surface temperature anomalies reveals that
both convection and increased upper tropospheric moisture occur over anomalously
warm water.  The development and movement of deep convection and increased
upper tropospheric moisture can clearly be traced during El Nino/Southern
Oscillation warm events (Figure 1).
<p>
Figure 1 shows HIRS12 anomaly time-longitude sections for three latitude
strips; 30-10N (Fig. 1a), 10N - 10S (Fig. 1b), and 10 - 30S (Fig. 1c).  In the
northern subtropics (Fig. 1a) the majority of the variability is centered
at 135W and extends from about 180 to 90W.  Variability near 135W at these
latitudes is generally out of phase with variability at 135W in the deep
tropics (Fig. 1b).  Thus, during the strong 1982/83 warm event, HIRS12 is
anomalously low (moist) in the tropics, but anomalously high (dry) in the
northern subtropics.  In the southern subtropics (Fig. 1c), the major
variability is found between 90E and 90W.  Again, this variability is
generally out of phase with variability in the tropics (Fig. 1b) but shows
propagation of anomalies to the northern subtropics, which shows standing
variability near 135W.
<p>
<A HREF="images/hirs.gif"><IMG alt="" SRC="images/hirs.tiny.gif"><BR> Figure 1: </A>
Mean monthly time/longitude sections for HIRS12 for (a) 30 - 10N,
(b) 10N - 10S, and (c) 10 - 30S.

<p>
<img alt="" src="images/go_back.gif"><a href="index.shtml">Satellite home page.</a>

<hr>
For informational queries contact
<address>Wesley Berg&lt;<a href="mailto:wkb@cdc.noaa.gov">wkb@cdc.noaa.gov</a>&gt;</address>
