<title>NOAA Climate Diagnostics Center (CDC): Overview</title>
</head>
<body>
<center>
<a href=http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/><img src=/cdc_images/banner.gif
alt="NOAA Climate Diagnostics Center"></a>
<h2><em>Advancing Understanding And Predictions of Climate Variability</em></h2>
<p>
<em><a href=/cdc/overview/>Contents</a></em> |
<em><a href=/cdc/overview/9697/>Recent Accomplishments</a></em> |
<em><a href=/cdc/overview/9697/milestones.html>FY97 Milestones</a></em> |
<em><a href=/cdc/overview/9596/>FY95/96 Information</a></em>
<p>
</center>
<hr>
<h3>CONTENTS:</h3>
<ul>
<li><a href="#mission">Mission</a>
<li><a href="#goals">Goals</a>
<li><a href="#data">Data Collection and Analysis</a>
<li><a href="#results">Results and Accomplishments</a>
<li><a href="#future">Future Work</a>
<li><a href="#refs">References</a>
<li><a href="#contacts">Contacts</a>
</ul>
<hr>
<a name=mission>
<h3>MISSION</h3>
</a>
The mission of the Climate Diagnostics Center
(CDC) is to identify the nature and causes for climate
variations on 
<a href=timeline.gif>time scales</a> ranging from a month to
centuries.
<p>
<center>
<a href=timeline.gif>
<img src=timeline_tiny.gif alt="Image of the CDC Research Timeline: Months to Centuries"></a>
</center>
<p>
<a name=nino>
The goal of this work is to</a>
develop the ability to predict important climate variations
on these time scales.  Short-term climate variations of
interest include major droughts and floods over the
continental U.S., and the global anomalies associated with
El Ni&ntilde;o-Southern Oscillation (ENSO).  These events
attract great public interest, and often have enormous
social and economic consequences.  On longer time scales,
basic research goals include identifying the causes for
decadal to centennial climate variations, and separating
natural variability from anthropogenically induced
climate changes in order to provide an improved scientific
basis for public planning and policy decisions.  CDC has
made considerable progress toward these goals through
a coordinated program of diagnostic and modeling
studies aimed at significantly advancing understanding
and predictions of climate variability.
<p>
<a name=goals>
<h3>GOALS</h3>
</a>
Specific goals of major subprojects within the Center include: 
<ul>
<li>Identifying key processes contributing to extreme
short-term climate events, including major droughts
and floods
  
<li>Advancing understanding and predictions of
ENSO
  
<li>Developing new diagnostic techniques to better
determine fundamental atmospheric quantities, such
as diabatic heating
  
<li>Improving monitoring and descriptions of climate
variability utilizing both surface and satellite data
  
<li>Diagnosing general circulation and operational
prediction model data to identify primary areas
where model improvements are needed
  
<li>Identifying major patterns of climate variability
on decadal and longer time scales
  
<li>Investigating the role of air-sea interactions in
modulating decadal-to-centennial variability.
  
</ul>  
Scientists at CDC employ a broad array of methods to
achieve these goals, including observational diagnostic
analyses, simple modeling studies, and analyses of
forecast experiments obtained from sophisticated models
of the atmosphere and oceans.  CDC studies increasingly
involve comparisons of observational and model data, an
activity essential for improving current research and
prediction models. 
This is one example of the more
general and fundamental 
<a href=flow_chart.gif>role that diagnostic studies
play</a> in linking together various disciplines, 
including observations and monitoring, theoretical research,
modeling, predictions, and, ultimately, applications.
<p>
<center>
<a href=flow_chart.gif><img src=flow_chart_tiny.gif 
alt="Illustration of the role of diagnostics studies"></a>
</center>
<p>
<a name=data>
<h3>DATA COLLECTION AND ANALYSIS</h3>
</a>
Major climate data set development projects at CDC
include the Comprehensive Ocean-Atmosphere Data Set
(<strong>COADS</strong>) and the Global Climate Perspectives System
(<strong>GCPS</strong>). Both are collaborative projects with the
<a href="http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/">National Climatic 
Data Center</a>.
The COADS project also
includes extensive cooperation with the 
<a href="http://http.ucar.edu/metapage.html">National
Center for Atmospheric Research</a> and the
<a href="http://cires.colorado.edu">
Cooperative Institute for Research in Environmental
Sciences (<strong>CIRES</strong>)</a>.  
These high-quality data
sets significantly improve NOAA's capabilities for
monitoring climatic trends, particularly in surface
temperatures and precipitation.  In addition, CDC
manages large observational and model data sets that are
frequently used in climate research studies within and
outside CDC, including the National 
Center for Environmental Prediction (NCEP)
reanalysis data set which, upon
completion, will have a volume of approximately 1.2
terabytes.  CDC's data management group is also a
leader in developing new techniques to simplify access to
and display of climate data for the larger scientific
community.  The CDC data holdings may be browsed via
the World Wide Web interface to the 
<A HREF="/cgi-bin/CDCData.pl">CDC data archives</a>. 
For further information on how to access CDC's research
data sets, contact 
<em>cdcdata@cdc.noaa.gov</em>.
<p>  

<a name=results>
<h3>RESULTS AND ACCOMPLISHMENTS</h3>
</a>
Some significant results and accomplishments 
are listed below:
<ul>
<li>An observational study examined the processes
contributing to the evolution of the extreme heat
wave-droughts in the Midwestern U.S. in 1980 and
1988.  The results showed that these extreme events
evolved in two stages, with the first or development
stage being forced from sources over the Pacific, and
the second stage due mainly to anomalous boundary
conditions (primarily reductions in soil moisture) in
the drought regions.  This suggests that, once
established, major heat wave-droughts tend to be
self-perpetuating (see the
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig3.html">
surface heat balance</a> illustration below).  
Another implication of this
study is that, in order to properly simulate or predict
long-term droughts, it will be necessary for
atmospheric prediction models to properly
incorporate the effects of land surface processes.
<p>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig3.html">
<img src="/cdc/overview/fig3_small.gif" align=middle 
alt=""></a>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig3.html">
Surface heat balance</a><br>
<p> 
<li>
<a name=enso>Several investigations considered various aspects
of ENSO. </a> One study identified the climatic impacts
of ENSO through observational analyses of 25 El
Ni&ntilde;o or "warm events" and 23 La Ni&ntilde;a or "cold
events."  The results showed that, during the
December through February period following the
development of a warm event, a large fraction of the
global tropics experiences above normal
temperatures.  Above normal temperatures also
dominate Alaska, the northern Midwestern states, and
most of Canada, while anomalously cold conditions
occur in the southeastern United States.  Nearly equal
and opposite signals are seen for cold events.  During
winter, warm event precipitation is enhanced over the
southeastern U.S. and southern South America, while
much of Australia, southern Africa and the Amazon
suffer precipitation deficits (the the
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig4.html">temperature</a>
and <a href="/cdc/overview/fig5.html">precipitation</a> anomaly
illustrations below).  Identification of
such relationships aids long-range weather forecasts,
since El Ni&ntilde;o is relatively predictable up to a year in
advance.
<p>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig4.html">
<img src="/cdc/overview/fig4_small.gif" 
alt="Temperature anomaly image">
</a>
<br>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig4.html">
Average temperature anomaly 
following the development of El Ni&ntilde;o.</a> 
<p>

<a href="/cdc/overview/fig5.html">
<img src="/cdc/overview/fig5_small.gif" alt="Precip anomaly image">
</a>
<br>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig5.html">
Average precipitation anomaly following the development of El Ni&ntilde;o.
</a>
<p>
</font>

<p>             
<li>A major research goal at CDC is to improve
predictive skill on seasonal and longer time scales.
One study evaluated the seasonal predictive skill of
two nearly identical versions of the National
Meteorological Center's climate model.  Skill was
evaluated by the model's ability to produce, on
average, seasonal circulation patterns over North
America (see the
<a href=/cdc/overview/fig6.html>composite anomaly</a>
illustrations below).  Although the two models had
identical sea surface temperatures, one was
significantly better for predicting seasonal
temperature anomalies.  These results indicate that
biases in current climate models can significantly
degrade forecast quality and reliability, and suggest
that further gains in seasonal forecast skill are likely
through continued development of climate models.
<p>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig6.html">
<img align=middle src="/cdc/overview/fig6_small.gif" 
alt=""></a>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig6.html">Composite temperature anomalies</a>
<p>                  
<li>In another study, a simple empirical dynamical
model of ENSO was developed that has predictive
skill at lead times of up to a year comparable to that
of comprehensive global coupled ocean-atmosphere
models.  In addition to providing tropical sea
surface temperature (SST) forecasts, this simple model
is being used to elucidate the basic mechanisms of
tropical SST evolution and to diagnose errors in the
more complicated coupled models.
<p>
<a href="/~cas/Cecile.forecast.html#maps">
<img alt="Current forecast image" align=middle src="/cdc/overview/penland.tiny.gif"></a>
<br>
<a href="/~cas/Cecile.forecast.html#maps">
Current forecasts of Pacific sea-surface temperature seasonal anomalies.
</a>
<p>             
<li>The ultimate cause of atmospheric motions is
spatial variations in heating and, therefore,
determining the location and intensity of atmospheric
heat sources is a fundamental problem in
meteorology.  Scientists at CDC have developed a
new method for estimating atmospheric heat sources
that provides very encouraging results, and are now
preparing a global heating data set for widespread
dissemination.  This data set should prove extremely
useful for verifying climate models and
satellite-derived estimates of precipitation, and
consequently improving our ability to monitor climate
variability and detect climate changes.
<p>
<li>In studies with 
<a href="/~climsat/">satellite data</a>, CDC scientists have
actively participated in the Global Energy and Water
Cycle Experiment (<strong>GEWEX</strong>).  As part of this work,
they have developed a new technique to improve
estimates of the  spatial and temporal variability of
atmospheric water vapor.  Their analyses show that
during the 1982-83 major ENSO event air in the
tropical upper troposphere became warmer, as
expected, but also drier, implying a negative feedback
effect from water vapor in the global warming sense.  
This differs from the IPCC consensus view
that the upper tropospheric water vapor feedback is
always large and positive, and emphasizes the
importance of such analyses in studies of climate and
global change.
<p>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig8.html"><img align=middle 
alt="HIRS Image" src="/cdc/overview/fig8_small.gif"></a>
<br>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig8.html">
HIRS channel 12 data from the NOAA polar orbiter
satellites.
</a>

<p>             
<li>Several studies at CDC have considered various
aspects of longer term climate variability.  Of
particular interest is the role of air-sea interactions in
climate and climate change.  Decadal and longer term
variations have been documented in winds and sea
surface temperature (SST) variability over the North
Atlantic, and thermal variations in the upper 500 m of
the North Pacific have been described since 1970 (see
figure below).  The latter study identified relationships between
the cooling trend observed in mid-Pacific SST's from
the 1970's to late 1980's and temperature anomalies in
the deeper ocean.  Another study showed how sea
surface temperature anomalies that formed near the
surface in winter could remain intact below surface
during summer, and then reappear at the surface the
following winter, thereby potentially influencing
interannual climate variability.
<p>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig9.html"><img align=middle 
alt="" src="/cdc/overview/fig9_small.gif"></a>
<a href="/cdc/overview/fig9.html">Time-depth plot 
of seasonal temperature anomalies</a>
</ul>             
             
<a name=future>
<h3>FUTURE WORK</h3>
</a>             
Future work at CDC will extend the research
activities described above, in direct support of three
primary NOAA Strategic Plan goals:  Advancing
Short-Term Forecast and Warning Services, Implementing
Seasonal to Interannual Forecasts, and Predicting Decadal
to Centennial Climate Changes.
<p> 
Studies of extreme events will examine the
relationships between these events and ENSO, the roles of
different physical processes in producing severe droughts
and floods, and the potential predictability of extreme
events.  Process studies will continue on ENSO and
air-sea interactions, along with collaborative studies with
the NCEP Coupled Model project to improve seasonal to
interannual climate predictions.  Long-term variability
studies will examine further the processes contributing to
decadal variability of the atmosphere-ocean system, as
well as decadal to centennial variability in precipitation
and other climate measures.  An important objective in
future work at CDC will be to identify and clarify the
linkages between climate variability on different time
scales; for example, how ENSO influences the occurrence
and duration of an extreme event such as a major drought
or flood, and the relationships between ENSO and
decadal-to-centennial variability.
             
<a name=refs>
<h3>REFERENCES</h3>
</a>
             
The CDC Progress Report for FY 1994 listed over 60
publications.  The following is a sampling of recent
publications illustrating CDC activities. A 
complete <a href="/cgi-bin/sort_pubs?pub_file_list"> 
CDC publications list</a> is also available. 
<ul> 
<li>Alexander, M.A., and C. Deser, 1995:  A mechanism for
the recurrence of winter midlatitude sea surface
temperature anomalies.  J. Phys. Oceanography, 25, 122-137.
             
<li>Diaz, H.F., and R.S. Pulwarty, 1994: An analysis of the
time scales of variability in centuries-long ENSO-sensitive
records.  Climatic Change, 26, 317-342.
             
<li>Kiladis,G. N., G.A. Meehl, and K. M. Weickmann:  Large
scale circulation associated with westerly wind bursts and
deep convection over the western equatorial Pacific.  J. of
Geophys. Res., 99, 18527-18544.
             
<li>Kumar, A., and M. P. Hoerling, 1995:  Prospects and
limitations of seasonal atmospheric general circulation
model predictions.  Bull. Amer. Meteor. Soc., 76, 335-345.
             
<li>Lyon, B. F., and R. M. Dole, 1995:  A comparative study
of the intense summer heat wave-droughts of 1980 and
1988. J. Climate,  8, 1658-1676.
             
<li>Penland, C., and T. Magorian, 1993: Prediction of Nio-3
sea surface temperatures using linear inverse modeling.
J. Climate, 6, 1067-1076.
             
<li>Sardeshmukh, P.D., 1993: The baroclinic chi-problem and
its application to the diagnosis of atmospheric heating
rates. J. Atmos. Sci., 50, 1099-1112.
             
<li>Wu, X, J. J. Bates and S. J. S. Khalsa, 1993:  A climatology
of the water vapor band brightness temperatures from
NOAA operational satellites.  J. Climate, 6 , 1282-1300.
             
</ul>

