<head>
<title>CDC Personal Home Pages: Suggestions and Guidelines</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>CDC Personal Home Pages: Suggestions and Guidelines</h1>
<hr>
Essentially, a <i>home page</i> is the multimedia, hypertext analog
of the <b>.plan</b> file used by the <code>finger(1)</code> program.
Currently, the CDC personal home pages follow a curriculum vitae
format. <p>
<h2>To create a home page for yourself:</h2>
<OL>
<LI> Create a directory named <b>public_html</b> in your home
directory (.i.e <b>~<em>user</em>/public_html</b>).  This directory will contain
all your hypertext documents written in 
<A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/General/Internet/WWW/HTMLPrimer.html">HTML</A>. 
<p>
<ul>
<li> <i>Make sure the directory is executable and readable by the group and
others (i.e. <code>drwxr-xr-x</code>).</i>  <p>
</ul>

<LI> In this <b>~<em>user</em>/public_html</b> directory, create a file called
<b>index.shtml</b>.  The contents of this file will be your home page.
If this is to be the page linked from the 
<a href=/cdc/people.shtml>CDC Staff page,</a> then 
it should roughly follow a vitae or resume format.
Additionally, it should not contain your photograph.
Look at <a href="people.shtml">other home 
pages</a> for examples and ideas.
You may also wish to review the 
<a href=http://www.w3.org/pub/WWW/Provider/Style/>Style Guide</a>
portion of the 
<a href=http://www.w3.org/pub/WWW/>World Wide Web Consortium</a>
Web pages, as well as the Web style guide articles produced by
the <a href=http://www.htmlhelp.com/>Web Design Group</a>.
<p>
<ul>
<li> <i>Make sure this file (and all others you reference) is readable by the
group and others (i.e. <code>-rw-r--r--</code>).</i> <p>
</ul>

<li>If you have publications which you would like to include in
<strong>both</strong> your personal web page as well as the 
<a href="/cgi-bin/sort_pubs?pub_file_list">CDC publications list</a>,
do the following:
<p>
<ul>
<li>Create a file called 
<em>pubs.html</em> in your public_html directory.
The contents of this file should look like this:
<blockquote>
&lt;html&gt;<br>
&lt;head&gt;<br>
&lt;title&gt;&lt;/title&gt;<br>
&lt;/head&gt;<br>
&lt;body&gt;<br>
&lt;ul&gt;<br>
&lt;li&gt;<em>first publication entry</em> &lt;p&gt;<br>
&lt;li&gt;<em>second publication entry</em> &lt;p&gt;<br>
&lt;li&gt;<em>etc.</em> &lt;p&gt;<br>
&lt;/ul&gt;<br>
&lt;/body&gt;<br>
&lt;/html&gt;<br>
</blockquote>
The <em>publication entries</em> should follow the 
<a href=ams.refs.html>format</a>
recommended by the American Meteorological Society.
<p>
<li>In your <em>index.shtml</em> file,
identify the point at which you'd like to show your
publications. At this location, 
add the following line to your <em>index.shtml</em> file:
<blockquote>
&lt;!--#include file="pubs.html"--&gt;
</blockquote>
<li>Notify 
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~jac/">Julia Collins</a>
that your publications are ready to be included in the
<a href="/cgi-bin/sort_pubs?pub_file_list">CDC publications list</a>.
</ul>
<p>
<LI> The 
<A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html">URL</A>
for your home page will be simply
<b>http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~<i>user/</i></b>. For example,
for the user <b>jac</b>, the proper url is
<b>http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~jac/</b>.
<p>

<li>Notify <a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~jac/">Julia Collins
</a> when your home page is ready.<p>
</OL>

<H2>Technical Information</H2>

Our server has the following default behavior: when a
<A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/demoweb/url-primer.html">URL</A>
references a directory (as opposed to a file), our server looks for
the file <b>index.shtml</b>. <p>

Our server globs the tilde, as in <b>~jac</b>, to mean
"look up the home directory of user <b>jac</b>, but look under
their <b>public_html</b> directory, if it exists."
<hr>
Thanks to the CIS Systems Staff at the
<a href="http://www.cis.ufl.edu/">University of Florida</a>
for the original version of this page. 
