   <LI><A  HREF="/~afl/vitae/full_vitae.html">Vitae          </A> <BR>

   <LI><A  HREF="/~afl/pubs.html">Publications                  </A> <BR>

   <LI><A  HREF="/~afl/presentations.html">Presentations        </A> <BR>
</UL>

<HR>

<H2> Current Work </H2>
Andy provides support for the scientific research efforts of 
<A HREF="/~rmd"> Dr. Randall Dole          </A> (Director of 
<A HREF="/"> NOAA/CDC                      </A> ) and 
<A HREF="/~jsw"> Dr. Jeffrey Whitaker      </A> (CIRES Research Associate).  
He performs computations and prepares visualizations for internal
review then publication of research relating to the predictive
quality of Atmospheric General Circulation Models.  He works
extensively with reanalysis data from 
<A HREF="http://dao.gsfc.nasa.gov/dao.home_page.html"> NASA/GSFC </A> and 
<A HREF="http://nic.fb4.noaa.gov:8000/">NCEP</A>, 
and with NCEP Ensemble Forecast data.  Common data formats are 
<A HREF="http://www.ncsa.uiuc.edu/SDG/Software/HDF/HDFIntro.html"> HDF</A>,
<A HREF="http://www.unidata.ucar.edu/packages/netcdf"> netCDF</A>, 
and raw binary (even 
<A HREF="ftp://ncardata.ucar.edu/libraries/grib/format_grib_94feb"> GRIB</A>).  
Software development is largely performed using 
<A HREF="http://k12.colostate.edu/workshop/workshop95/mon/intro.fortran.fm.html"> 
FORTRAN </A> and 
<A HREF="http://www.rsinc.com"> IDL</A>.
Andy is also familiar with other software (including freeware) that is
available for the 
<A HREF="http://www.eecs.nwu.edu/unix.html"> Unix </A> operating system. 
<P>

Andy's research interests have lead him to a study of atmospheric
processes on both the meso- and global- space scales.
Research for the Masters Degree lead him to understand some of the
difficulties inherent in applying simple two-dimensional
frontal models to real-world (i.e., three-dimensional)
situations.  These difficulties have, to some extent, been
addressed by application of the 
<A HREF="/~afl/abstracts/thesis.html"> psi-vector technique </A>
to diagnose 3-D frontal circulations. Andy had the opportunity of
working with an oceanographer at NASA/GSFC.  This opportunity taught him to
appreciate the synergistic role of the 
<A HREF="/~afl/abstracts/schopf_loughe.html"> ocean-atmosphere system </A>.  
Now he is studying the predictability of general
circulation models which are run in both "reanalysis" and
"forecast" modes.  The reanalysis runs are interesting
because of the long time period over which they provide
consistent, analyzable data, but the ensemble prediction runs
offer a view to the future of numerical weather prediction. 
<BR>  

<HR>
