<h2>Education</h2>

<ul>
<li> Ph.C.,  Atmospheric Sciences, <a href="http://www.washington.edu/">University of Washington</a>,  March 1982.
<li> M.S.,  Physics, <a href="http://www.ufl.edu/">University of Florida</a>,  August 1978.
<li> B.S.,  Physics, <a href="http://www.ufl.edu/">University of Florida</a>,  August 1976.
</ul>

<hr>
<h2>Related Links</h2>

<ul>
<li><a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~drm/home.html">Personal home page</a><br>
<li><a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~drm/vitae.html">Vitae</a><br>
<li><a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~drm/publications.shtml">Publications</a><br>
<li><a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/~drm/publications.shtml#presentations">Presentations</a><br>
</ul>

<hr>
<p>
My background is in Physics (University of Florida), Meteorology (University of Washington), and
Oceanography (Jet Propulsion Laboratory).  I became interested in systems administration around
the time Unix workstations first became popular (circa 1987).  I found that I enjoyed configuring 
computer systems to better serve the needs of the scientists with whom I worked.  About the same
time, I also became interested in the problems associated with the analysis and display of large, 
cumbersome geophysical data sets, so I wrote my own rather primitive data visualization package 
for use on a Sun 3/60.  These two interests, systems management and data management, have been 
the focus of my professional activities ever since.
<p>
I now serve as CDC's Director of Computing and Network Services, with overall responsibility 
for the provision of state-of-the-art computational and network facilities in support
of CDC's scientific mission.  As a Department of Commerce appointed Contracting Officer, 
I also act as the chief procurement official for the majority of CDC's computer-related purchases.  
I am the technical supervisor of the computer systems support staff and have considerable
expertise in systems integration and long range planning.  I collaborate with the broader NOAA 
community on many technical issues through my participation on the ERL Technical Committee on 
Computing Resources and the NOAA-Boulder Network Working Group.  
<p>
In the area of data management, I helped create CDC's Climate Research Data Center, which has
evolved over the years into our on-line data service available through the Web.  I am the 
technical supervisor of CDC's data management group, which includes our Webmaster and individuals
associated with the ingest and redistribution of the NCEP/NCAR Reanalysis data set.  I am active 
in the American Meteorological Society's annual IIPS (data management) conference and also serve 
as the OAR representative to the ESDIM Program, which helps coordinate NOAA's agency-wide data 
management strategy.  For my efforts to promote use of the Web throughout the agency, I was named 
"OAR Employee of the Year" for 1995.
<p>
