<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE> Jeff Whitaker's home page </TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<center>
<h1>Jeffrey S. Whitaker</h1>
<strong>
  <A HREF="http://cires.colorado.edu"> CIRES </A>, Campus Box 449  <BR>
  <a href=http://www.colorado.edu>University of Colorado</a>    <BR>
  Boulder, CO 80309-0449         <BR>
  Voice: (303) 492-2382       <BR>
  FAX: (303) 497-7013       <br>
  office location:  RL2, room 242 <br>
E-mail: <a href=mailto://jsw@cdc.noaa.gov>jsw@cdc.noaa.gov</a>
</strong>
</center>
<br>
<HR>
<br>
<li><B>B.A.-Earth and Planetary Sciences</B>
<A HREF="http://www.jhu.edu/~eps/">Johns Hopkins University,</A> 1984.<BR>
<li><B>M.S.-Meteorology</B> 
<A HREF="http://www.met.fsu.edu">Florida State University,</A> 1986. <BR>
Thesis title: <I>A diagnostic study of explosive oceanic cyclogensis using
a mesoscale model simulation.</I>
<li><B>Ph.D.-Meteorology</B>
<A HREF="http://www.met.fsu.edu">Florida State University,</A> 1990. Advisor:
Albert Barcilon. <BR>
Thesis title: <I>On the initiation of surface cyclones by upper tropospheric
disturbances.</I>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<br>
<li><a href="/~jsw/vitae.html">Vitae</a>
<li><a href="/~jsw/pubs.html">Publications</a>
<li><a href="/~jsw/presentations.html">Presentations</a>
<br>
<br>
<hr>
<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 3.2//EN">
<HTML>
<BODY>
<br>
Currently, my research at CDC is focused in these areas:
<br><br>
<li> <strong> Storm track dynamics.</strong> <br><br>

"Storm tracks" are geographically localized regions of high-frequency, synoptic-scale eddy activity, such as those observed off the East coasts of Asia and North America in winter.  Since arriving at CDC, I have been studying the sensitivity of storm tracks to various aspects of the large-scale, low-frequency flow in which they are imbedded. <a href="/~jsw/Abstracts/jsw+rmd1.abstract.html">Whitaker and Dole </a> (1995, <i> J. Atmos. Sci. </i>, 889-907) examined the role of large-scale zonal variations of baroclinicity, horizontal deformation, and uniform translation in the organization of storm tracks in an idealized model. <a href="/~jsw/Abstracts/jsw+pds1.abstract.html">Whitaker and Sardeshmukh </a> (1997, <i> J. Atmos. Sci. </i>, to appear) used a two-level quasi-geostrophic model linearized about the observed 400 and 800 mb wintertime flow and forced with Gaussian white noise to simulate the statistics of observed synoptic-scale transient eddies. The
model not only produced realistic eddy <A HREF="/~jsw/presentations/JSW+PDS1talk.9606/slide5.gif">streamfunction
variance</A> maxima in the Pacific and Atlantic storm tracks , but also
variations in their <A HREF="/~jsw/presentations/JSW+PDS1talk.9606/slide15.gif">relative
strengths</A> through the fall, winter and spring seasons. The model was
also successful in producing realistic distributions of the associated
eddy <A HREF="/~jsw/presentations/JSW+PDS1talk.9606/slide7.gif">vorticity</A>
and <A HREF="/~jsw/presentations/JSW+PDS1talk.9606/slide8.gif">heat </A> fluxes.  
<br><br>
<li><strong> Feedback between high-frequency (synoptic scale) and low-frequency (planetary scale) motions. </strong><br><br>

Low-frequency, large-scale motions in the extratropics are sustained, in part, through fluxes of heat and momentum by high-frequency, synoptic-scale eddies.  Since the low-frequency motions also act to organize synoptic eddies into storm tracks, the interaction between the two scales of motion is quite nonlinear.  We are using the storm track model described by  <a href="/~jsw/Abstracts/jsw+pds1.abstract.html">Whitaker and Sardeshmukh </a> to investigate what large scale flow patterns are most
effective in organizing transient eddy fluxes of heat and momentum which
act to <I>reinforce</I> the large scale flow pattern itself. Ultimately,
we hope to use the storm track model as a basis for the parameterization of high-frequency
transient eddies in a reduced model of large-scale, low-frequency variability
in the atmosphere.
<br><br>
<li><strong> Ensemble prediction.</strong> <br><br>

For lead times beyond a few days, numerical weather prediction should be thought of in probabilistic, instead of deterministic terms.  That is, the focus shifts from producing a single weather map (reflecting the future state of the atmosphere given the initial state), to producing an array of weather maps (reflecting a range of possible future states given a range of equally likely initial states).  The diversity of possible future states is a function of forecast lead time and the errors in the observing system (i.e. the diversity of equally likely initial states). Ensemble prediction is an attempt to calculate the range of possible future states by performing multiple numerical predictions starting from a range of different (ideally, equally likely) initial states. At CDC, we have been obtaining and archiving ensemble predictions produced by <a href="http://www.ncep.noaa.gov">NCEP</a> (the National Centers for Environmental Prediction).  A detailed <a href = "http://sgi62.wwb.noaa.gov:8080/ens/ens_info.html">description</a> of NCEP's ensemble forecasting scheme is available on the web. An active area of research at CDC involves studying how to extract useful information from these data, particularly relating to the problem of how to forecast <a href = "/cdc/overview/extreme">extreme short-term climate anomalies</a> more than a week in advance.  Real time <a href = "/~map/maproom/ENS/ens.html">ensemble forecast products</a> are produced from the NCEP ensemble data here at CDC.  In addition to studies involving the operational NCEP ensemble data, we are investigating alternative strategies for ensemble prediction using idealized models.  Among the questions we are trying to answer with simple models are; 1) what is the optimal way to create initial states for ensemble prediction?, 2) what is the effect of model errors (as opposed to initial condition errors)?, and 3) how can we extract the most useful information from the ensemble? (particularly at long forecast leads when the "signal to noise" ratio is small).
<br><br>


</BODY>
</HTML>

