<head>
<title>
GFDL-University Consortium R30 Model Experiments
</title>
</head>
<body>
<h1>GFDL-University Consortium R30 Model Experiments</h1>
<hr size=4>
<p>
The NOAA/Universities Consortium R30 experiments run to date are listed below.
See specific documentation for each experiment for details.
<p>
<hr size=4>
<p>
All R30 experiments have the following characteristics in common:
<ul>
<li>R30 truncation, 
<li>predicted clouds, 
<li>fixed sst, 
<li>gravity wave drag.
</ul><p>

<img alt = "o" src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc_images/blueball.gif">
40-year Seasonal Experiment
<ul>
<li>model is a version of the 9-level GFDL climate model
<li>climatological prescribed SST and sea ice,
     interpolated in time from monthly means.
<li>Nine levels in the vertical.
<li>seasonally-varying insolation and ozone.
<li>Data format: packed IEEE
<li>Dataset size: ~8.4 GB 
<li>See <em>R30L9_seasonal_40yr_doc</em> for details.
<li>contact: pjp@gfdl.gov
  </ul>

<img alt = "o" src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc_images/blueball.gif">
17-year Seasonal Experiment: A new model with 14 vertical levels
<ul>
<li>This model is essentially an improved version of the GFDL R30
       9-level climate model. The most significant improvement is the
       increase in vertical resolution, but other changes have also
       been made.
<li>Data format:  packed IEEE
<li>Dataset size: ~3.7 GB
<li>See <em>R30L14_seasonal_doc</em> for details.
<li>contact: pjp@gfdl.gov
</ul>
  
<img alt = "o" src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc_images/blueball.gif">
Perpetual Experiments<p>
SST, sea ice, ozone , insolation and soil moisture fixed at values
       corresponding to a particular date of the year
       (snow depth is not fixed).<p>
<ul>
<li>3000 day integration of perpetual July 16 using the 14-level model
<ul>
<li>Daily data available for a subset of model variables.
<li>3000-day means available for all other variables.
<li>Dataset size: ~1.6 GB
<li>See <em>R30L14_perpetual_jul_doc</em> for details.
<li>contact: pjp@gfdl.gov
</ul>
</ul>

The following were run with the 9-level model:
<ul>
<li>2100 day integrations of perpetual Jan 16 and July 16
<ul>
<li>Daily data available for a subset of model variables.
<li>100-day means available for all other variables.
<li>Dataset size: ~1.6 GB for each integration
<li>See <em>R30L9_perpetual_jan_and_jul_doc</em> for details.
<li>contact: pjp@gfdl.gov
</ul>
<br>
<li>2000 day integrations of perpetual model for these dates:
       Mar 16, Apr 15, May 1, May 16
<ul>
<li>All data available as 100 day means.
<li>Dataset size: ~85 MB for each integration
<li>See <em>R30L9_perpetual_mar_apr_may_doc</em> for details.
<li>contact: pjp@gfdl.gov
</ul>
<br>
<li>30 day integration of perpetual Jan 16 with output saved every time step.
<ul>
<li>Overlaps with 2100 day integration for perpetual Jan 16
<li>120 time steps per day
<li>Not all model variables are saved, but all those that are 
	   are given every time step.
<li>Dataset size: ~2.9 GB
<li>See <em>R30L9_every_time_step_doc</em> for details.
<li>contact: pjp@gfdl.gov
</ul>
     
</ul>
 
<img alt = "o" src="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc_images/blueball.gif">
Idealized Experiments done with 9-level model
<ul>
<li>total ocean surface with prescribed SSTs
<li>annual mean insolation. <p>
<li>2025-day Integrations with Zonal SSTs
<ul>
<li>Four integrations have been performed:
<ul>
   <li>A control with SSTs approximating realistic
 	  annual mean temperatures.
   <li>An integration with tropical temperatures increased
 	  above those of the control.
   <li>An integration with high-latitude temperatures increased
 	  above those of the control.
   <li>An integration with global tempertures uniformally inceased
 	  above those of the control.
</ul>
	  
<li>Data format: IEEE, not packed.
<li>Dataset size: ~1.6 GB for each integration
<li>See <em>R30L9_idealized_with_zonal_ssts_doc</em> for details.
<li>contact: pjp@gfdl.gov
</ul>
<p>
<li>1440-day Integration with Non-Zonal SST
<ul>
    <li>One integration has been performed:
	   A cold area serving as a surrogate for a cold winter 
	   continent is inserted into both hemispheres at mid latitudes.
	   Outside these cold areas the SSTs are fixed to the same
	   values used in the zonal control integration described above.
	   
    <li>Data format: IEEE, not packed.
    <li>Dataset size: ~1.1 GB
    <li>See <em>R30L9_idealized_with_non-zonal_ssts_doc</em> for details.
    <li>contact: pjp@gfdl.gov
</ul>
</ul>

<hr size=4>
<address>
<a href="/gfdl/">The GFDL-University Consortium</a><br>
webmaster@cdc.noaa.gov
</address>
