<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>NCEP Atlas: calculation details</TITLE>
<!-- Changed by: Cathy Smith, 17-Apr-1996 -->
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF">
<center>
<a href="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov">
<IMG alt="Climate Daignostics Center" SRC="http://www.cdc.noaa.gov/cdc_images/banner.gif"></a>
</center>
<H2>NCEP(NMC) Reanalysis Atlas</H2>

<FONT Size=5>

Select output type for calculation details:</font></br>
<p>
<BLOCKQUOTE>

<FONT Size=4><a href="#Mean">Total Monthly Means</a></br>
<a href="#Yearseas">Monthly Means by year</a></br>
<a href="#Inter">Interannual standard deviation (by month)</a></br>
<a href="#Intra">Total Standard deviation (by month)</a></br>
<a href="#diurn">Diurnal Cycle by Month</a></br>
<a href="#eof">EOF's by Month</a></br>
</BLOCKQUOTE>
<DL>
<DT><B>Total Seasonal Means</B><A NAME="Means"> </A>
<DD> Seasonal means are calculated by averaging the 4 times daily data for
January 1979 to December 1995  over all years (Feb 29 is not used) for each of the four seasons. Seasons are defined as Mar-Apr-May, Jun-Jul-Aug, Sep-Oct-Nov and Dec-Jan-Feb. Thus,
each season is averaged for 9 full years:<br>
<center>
<img src="eqn1.gif"><br></center><br>
Seasonal mean values of surface pressure were used to mask out any grid
points below the surface.<p>
<dt><B>Seasonal Yearly Means</B><A NAME="Yearseas"> </A>
<dd>Seasonal means are calculated by averaging the 4 times daily data for each of 4 seasons of each year from March 1985 to Feb 1993 (Feb 29 is not used). Seasons are defined as Mar-Apr-May, Jun-Jul-Aug, Sep-Oct-Nov and Dec-Jan-Feb. There are a total of 36 seasonal values for each file:<br>

<center><img src="eqn2.gif"><br></center>
<p>
<DT><B>Seasonal Transient Flux Means</B><A NAME="nonfiltflux"> </A>
<DD> Seasonal transient fluxes are calculated by averaging the 4 times daily data for
March 1985 to Feb 1993  over all years (Feb 29 is not used) for each of the four seasons the quantity x'y' where x' is the difference from the total seasonal
mean X and y' is the difference from the total seasonal mean Y. Seasons are defined as Mar-Apr-May, Jun-Jul-Aug, Sep-Oct-Nov and Dec-Jan-Feb. Thus,
each season is averaged for 9 full years.<br>
<center><img src="eqn5.gif"><br></center><p>
<DT><B>Monthly Means</B><A NAME="Monmean"> </A>
<DD> Monthly means are calculated by averaging the 4 times daily data for
March 1985 to Feb 1993  over all years (Feb 29 is not used) for each month.
Eight full years go into each month.<p>
<dt><B>Interannual standard deviation</B><A NAME="Inter"> </A>
<dd>Values for each season are calculated by summing over the squared difference between each years' seasonal mean and the total seasonal mean for each gridpoint. That is:<br><center>
<img src="eqn3.gif"><p></center>
<dt><B>Total standard deviation</B><A NAME="Intra"> </A>
<dd>Values for each month are calculated by summing the squared difference between the value averaged for one day and the monthly mean for that year for all years.  That is:<br><center>
<img src="eqn4.gif"><p>
</center>
<dt><B>Diurnal Cycle by Month</B><A NAME="diurn"> </A>
<dd>Values for each of the 4 times (0z,6z,12z,18z) are averaged over all
years for each month for each separate level. A total mean is calculated 
for each month and the anomalies from these means for the 0z,6z,12z and 18z 
means are stored. Four months are presented in the atlas; January, April, 
July and October.<p>
<dt><B>EOF's of monthly anomalies for the Norther Hemisphere</B><A NAME="eof"> </A>
<dd>EOF's for each month were calculated from 17 years of anomaly data. Data for
the Northern Hemisphere ONLY was used and a cosine weighting was applied to correct
for the decrease in longitude spacing with latitude.  EOF's were calculated separately
for each level. What is plotted is the correlation between the principal component
time series and the data at each grid point for the entire globe. The correlations 
were "corrected" to match the sign of the 1000mb level so that vertical plots could be 
made. However, there is no guarantee that the first EOF of one level will match the 
first EOF's of the other levels. In most cases, though, the correlation is quite high;
especially in winter.
</DL>
</font>
